@node "About Manager"

@toc "MANAGER menu"

@xref "About PHOENIX"

@{U}1.1.1  About Manager                                   PHOENIX Manager@{u}



Activating this menu entry brings up a dialog-box showing the authors

who created and translated the program. Clicking on the @{B}@{Info ignore}...@{b} box

provides some further information about its development.



@{B}The purpose of Manager@{b}



The Manager program serves for the acquisition and evaluation of data

of a database. Such a database must have been created beforehand with

the @{Designer ignore} program.



In detail, you can perform the following tasks in Manager:



   ˘ Input of data records

   ˘ Modification of data records

   ˘ Deletion of data records

   ˘ Searching of data records

   ˘ Retrieval of data records

   ˘ Display of data records in table form (as a list)

   ˘ Display of data records in mask form

   ˘ Output of tables to a file

   ˘ Printing of tables

   ˘ Exporting of data records

   ˘ Importing of data records

   ˘ Creation and evaluation of queries

   ˘ Sorting of tables

   ˘ Creation and output of reports and templates

   ˘ Automatic calculation of data

   ˘ Setting and modifying the password

   ˘ Display of information about the database, table or indices

   ˘ Launching @{Designer ignore}

   ˘ Data exchange via the GEM-clipboard

   ˘ Setting of various system parameters



The tasks listed above can be performed individually, but to a large

extent also simultaneously in parallel. A multitasking kernel has

been implemented in the Manager which makes it possible to perform

all longer-lasting operations in the background. Up to six such

processes, also called tasks, can run in parallel. This makes it

possible, for instance, to print out a long list from a table while

searching for the address of a contact in another table (of any

database) so that you can contact him.



@{B}Launching the Manager@{b}

The Manager is started by double-clicking on the MANAGER.PRG icon or

filename. At launch the following files should be present on the

floppy disk or hard drive partition:

- MANAGER.PRG

- MANAGER.RSC

- MANAGER.INF

- MANAGER.HYP - the ST-Guide hypertext with online help for Manager



MANAGER.INF contains the default settings for the program. If this

file is missing, then the Manager will create one from the settings

you make in the program. When Manager is terminated, the .INF file

will be created provided the checkbox @{B}@{Save ignore} automatically@{b} is switched

on in the @{"Configuration dialog-box" LINK "Dialogbox Konfiguration"}.



If no databases are loaded, then at launch the Open command will be

performed.



Further information:



About PHOENIX



@endnode





