@node "Open"

@toc "File menu"

@{U}1.2.1  Open [^O], [F2]                                 PHOENIX Manager@{u}



Activating this menu entry (or its equivalent in the function key bar

or the @{"second icon on the desktop" LINK "Schreibtisch des Managers"}), opens a new database, or one or

more items that have been selected by clicking on them and so are

displayed in inverse video. As an alternative, with a window open, a

double-click on an item using the left mouse button will open it.



If one or more data records in a @{"table window" LINK "Tabellen-Fenster"} are selected, then

this corresponds to using the Edit data command, although there are

exceptions from this for the special tables @{"query-list" LINK "Abfrageliste-Fenster"}, @{"template-list" LINK "Reportliste-Fenster"}

and @{"calculation-list" LINK "Rechnenliste-Fenster"}. If there are data records selected in one of

these, then they can be modified in their own special way (e.g. with

query by example).



If no item has been selected, then a new database can be opened. A

fileselector-box appears offering all files with the suffix .IND for

selection. After a file is chosen, the @{"Open database dialog-box" LINK "Dialogbox Datenbank îffnen"} will

appear, where you can set some parameters for the database.



@endnode





@node "Close"

@toc "File menu"

@{U}1.2.2  Close [^U], [F3]                                PHOENIX Manager@{u}



The topped window of the program will be closed when this menu entry

(or its equivalent in the function key bar) is activated.



If there were any changes made to its data, then a safety query

appears offering the option of saving the data first.



If no window is open any more, then the command can no longer be used

and is therefore disabled.



@endnode





@node "Close DB"

@toc "File menu"

@{U}1.2.3  Close DB [^B], [F4]                             PHOENIX Manager@{u}



The current database will be closed immediately when this menu entry

(or its equivalent in the function key bar) is activated.



Before it is closed, all windows that belong to this database will be

closed. If there were any changes made to the data in one of its

windows, then a safety query appears offering the option of saving

the data first.



If a process is running on the database that is to be closed, then

this database can not be closed before the process is terminated by

force or normally.



If all databases are closed, then the command can no longer be used

and is therefore disabled.



@endnode





@node "Save"

@toc "File menu"

@{U}1.2.4  Save [^S]                                       PHOENIX Manager@{u}



A defined query, a report, a calculation, a batch or a template will

be saved under its current name when this menu entry is activated.



If no name has been defined as yet, then the Save as command will be

called.



@endnode





@node "Save as"

@toc "File menu"

@{U}1.2.5  Save as [^M]                                    PHOENIX Manager@{u}



A defined query, a report, a calculation, a batch or a template can

be saved under a name of your choice.



When you select this menu entry, the dialog-box opens

that shows all items saved to date in a scrollable listbox, or lets

you enter a new name.



@endnode





@node "Export"

@toc "File menu"

@{U}1.2.6  Export [^E]                                     PHOENIX Manager@{u}



A table can be output as a binary file to a hard or floppy disk. The

command refers either to a selected table or selected data records, or

to the current table. If it is applied to a selected table or selected

data records, then only the fields that are curently displayed in the

table will be exported.



After activating this command a fileselector-box appears in which

you have to enter the desired filename.



The export of the table runs as a process in the background. You

can make certain settings for the table beforehand which affect the

appearance of the written data. These settings can be made in the

dialog-box that opens when you activate the @{"Im/Export parameters" LINK "Dialogbox Im/Export-Parameter"}

command.



@{I}Note:@{i}

Because the command can be applied to a selected table, it is

possible to export data from tables that are not otherwise

selectable. For instance, it is not possible to select the table

QUERY @{LIST ignore} in the @{"database toolbox" LINK "Schreibtisch des Managers" "Database toolbox"} because it is not displayed there

(we are dealing with an internal table). If, however, a query-list is

output (via the @{B}List@{b} command), then it can first be iconized,

subsequently selected and then exported.



@autorefoff

The QUERY LIST, REPORT LIST, CALCULATION LIST and BATCH LIST tables

@autorefon

are exported in a binary form by default, because usually they have

several line-dividers in the data record. If you want to export them

as ASCII files despite of this, you have to change the suffix BIN in

the fileselector-box to the suffix ASC.



@endnode





@node "Import"

@toc "File menu"

@xref "Export"

@{U}1.2.7  Import [^I]                                     PHOENIX Manager@{u}



A table can be read in as a text or binary file from a hard or floppy

disk. This command refers either to a selected table or selected data

records, or to the current table. If it is applied to a selected

table or selected data records, then only the fields that are

curently displayed in the table will be imported.



After activating this command a fileselector-box appears in which you

have to enter the desired filename.



The import of the table runs as a process in the background. You can

make certain settings for the table beforehand which affect the

appearance of the data. These settings can be made in the dialog-box

that opens when you activate the @{"Im/Export parameters" LINK "Dialogbox Im/Export-Parameter"} command.



@{I}Note:@{i}

Because the command can be applied to a selected table, it is possible

to export data from tables that are not otherwise selectable (see

Export).



@endnode





@node "Disk output"

@toc "File menu"

@{U}1.2.8  Disk output [^S]                                PHOENIX Manager@{u}



A table can be output as a text file to a hard or floppy disk. This

command refers either to a selected table or selected data records,

or to the current table.



After activating this command a fileselector-box appears in which you

have to enter the desired filename.



The output of the table runs as a process in the background. You

can make certain settings for the table beforehand which affect the

appearance of the table. These settings can be made in the dialog-box

that opens when you activate the @{"Page format" LINK "Dialogbox Seitenformat"} command.



@endnode





@node "Print"

@toc "File menu"

@{U}1.2.9  Print [^P]                                      PHOENIX Manager@{u}



A table can be output as a text file to a printer. This command

refers either to a selected table or selected data records, or to the

topped window or current table. However, the printing of the topped

window applies only to the @{"editor window" LINK "Editor-Fenster"}, the @{"report window" LINK "Bericht-Fenster"} and the

@{"template window" LINK "Report-Fenster"}.



The output of the table runs as a process in the background. You

can make certain settings for the table beforehand which affect the

appearance of the table. These settings can be made in the dialog-box

that opens when you activate the @{"Page format" LINK "Dialogbox Seitenformat"} command.



For printing, all the settings apply that can be defined with the

@{"Printer parameters" LINK "Dialogbox Drucker-Parameter"} command (except for a report, which uses NVDI for

producing hard copies).



@endnode





@node "Quit"

@toc "File menu"

@{U}1.2.10  Quit [^Q]                                      PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This command terminates the session. If there are still some unsaved

changes of data records, reports, queries, calculation definitions

etc., corresponding safety queries willl be displayed. This should

ensure that no data is lost accidentally. Results of queries, i.e.

@{"table-clipboards" LINK "table-clipboard window"}, are not saved.



When the Manager is quit, the file MANAGER.INF will be created or

updated provided @{B}@{Save ignore} automatically@{b} in the @{"Configuration dialog-box" LINK "Dialogbox Konfiguration"}

is switched on.



@endnode





