@node "Undo"

@toc "Edit menu"

@{U}1.3.1  Undo [^Z], [Undo]                               PHOENIX Manager@{u}



Activating this command reverses the last action you performed.

This can be achieved also by pressing the [Undo] key.



Whether the last action @{I}can@{i} be reversed depends on the topped window

and current circumstances. If the menu item is selectable (i.e. not

greyed out like this: @{G}Undo@{g}) then it can be applied.



In the description for @{"table windows" LINK "Tabellen-Fenster"} it is specified under which

circumstances the @{B}Undo@{b} command works when a table window is active.

The data record that was deleted last can be restored  with @{B}Undo@{b}.

The reinsertion of a deleted data record can also be rescinded, which

corresponds to a renewed deletion of the record.



@{I}Note:@{i}

The deletion and reinsertion of data records via the @{B}Undo@{b} command

always affects only the last data record, even if several data records

were deleted.



@endnode





@node "Cut"

@toc "Edit menu"

@{U}1.3.2  Cut [^X]                                        PHOENIX Manager@{u}



The selected items can be cut from the display by activating this

command. They will be copied to an internal buffer, so that they can

be inserted in another place.



However, this only applies to items that are in memory, so not for

data records, for instance.



@endnode





@node "Copy"

@toc "Edit menu"

@{U}1.3.3  Copy [^C]                                       PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This command works like the Cut command, but the original item will

remain in place. If data records are selected in a @{"table window" LINK "Tabellen-Fenster"},

then these can not be copied.



@endnode





@node "Paste"

@toc "Edit menu"

@{U}1.3.4  Paste [^V]                                      PHOENIX Manager@{u}



Activating this command inserts the last item @{"cut" LINK "Cut"} or @{"copied" LINK "Copy"}.

Depending on the window and  context, this can produce different

effects. If a data record was cut from a @{"table window" LINK "Tabellen-Fenster"}, then it can

be reinserted with this, of course.



In addition, all data records that were deleted previously can be put

back again; this can be done either individually by selecting them in

the @{"wastebin window" LINK "Papierkorb-Fenster"}, or all of them by selecting the @{"wastebin icon" LINK "Papierkorb-Sinnbild"}

and then activating this command.



@{I}Note:@{i}

If a database is reorganised, it will forget all previously deleted

data records, so that these can no longer be restored.



@endnode





@node "Delete"

@toc "Edit menu"

@{U}1.3.5  Delete [^D]                                     PHOENIX Manager@{u}



The selected items will be deleted without copying them into a buffer

when you activate this command. If data records in a table are

selected, then they can be restored via the @{"wastebin window" LINK "Papierkorb-Fenster"}.



@endnode





@node "Select all"

@toc "Edit menu"

@{U}1.3.6  Select all [^A]                                 PHOENIX Manager@{u}



On activating this menu entry all items of the current window will be

selected, provided that they are selectable.



In a @{"table window" LINK "Tabellen-Fenster"}, all data records visible in the window will be

selected. If no window is open, then all items that are present on

@{"the Manager's desktop" LINK "Schreibtisch des Managers"} will be selected.



So, say, if all @{"table icons" LINK "Tabellen-Sinnbild"} and all @{"table-clipboard icons" LINK "Tabellenklemmbrett-Sinnbild"} are to be

removed from the desktop, then you must use the @{B}Select all@{b} command

followed by the @{B}Remove@{b} command. A prerequisite for this is that no

other window is open at the time. In addition all processes that may

be running will be removed, unless they were deselected again.



@endnode





