@node "Cycle windows"

@toc "Edit menu"

@{U}1.3.10  Cycle windows [^W]                             PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This command allows the user to switch between the opened windows of

the active program. This always places the lower-most window right

at the top.



@{I}Tip:@{i}

Alternatively, [Alternate]+[Esc], [Control]+[Esc] or [Control]+[W]

key presses are allowed and produce the same result!



@endnode





@node "Open table"

@toc "Edit menu"

@{U}1.3.11  Open table [^T]                                PHOENIX Manager@{u}



A new @{"table window" LINK "Tabellen-Fenster"} will be opened when you activate this command. It

displays the data records with the values set at the time of opening

the @{"database toolbox" LINK "Schreibtisch des Managers" "Database toolbox"}:

- The current database

- The current table

- The current index

- The current sorting direction

- The currently set font



The font can be set by using the Font command in the Parameters menu.

The handling of this window is described in the @{"table window" LINK "Tabellen-Fenster"} section.



@endnode





@node "Edit data"

@toc "Edit menu"

@{U}1.3.12  Edit data [F10]                                PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This menu entry (or its equivalent in the function key bar and also

the mask icon in the @{"desktop" LINK "Schreibtisch des Managers"} and @{"table window" LINK "Tabellen-Fenster"} menu bars) offers a

number of functions:



If data records of a table window are selected, then they can be

modified. If @{"table icons" LINK "Tabellen-Sinnbild"} or @{"table-clipboard icons" LINK "Tabellenklemmbrett-Sinnbild"} are selected, then

the data records of these icons can be edited.



If no items are selected, then the data records of the current table

in the current database can be modified.



When editing data records, masks for this table defined in @{Designer ignore}

will open. In a @{"mask window" LINK "Masken-Fenster"} you can modify the data records, i.e.

change or delete them, or input new items.



@endnode





@node "Remove"

@toc "Edit menu"

@{U}1.3.13  Remove [^R]                                    PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This command can be activated when @{"table icons" LINK "Tabellen-Sinnbild"} or data records in a

table-clipboard window have been selected.

You can use this command also when a @{"process icon" LINK "Prozeû-Sinnbild"} is selected.



If any data records are selected, then they will be removed from the

table-clipboard without being physically deleted. If table icons have

been selected then these too are removed from the desktop without

deletion.



If process icons are selected then these processes will be terminated.

A safety query appears before the termination.



@endnode





@node "Remove range"

@toc "Edit menu"

@{U}1.3.14  Remove range [^L]                              PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This command opens the @{"Remove range dialog-box" LINK "Dialogbox Bereich entfernen"}.



This makes it possible to remove a given range of data records from a

table-clipboard window. It can only be applied when such a window is

topped and contains at least one record.



@endnode





@node "Empty wastebin"

@toc "Edit menu"

@{U}1.3.15  Empty wastebin [^H]                            PHOENIX Manager@{u}



On activating this menu entry the wastebin will be cleared. Following

this it is no longer possible to access deleted data records. The

emptying of the wastebin runs as a process in the background and can

be interrupted at any time (see description of @{"process window" LINK "Prozeû-Fenster"}).



Before the actual clearance a safety query appears, which you have to

confirm for the action to go ahead.



@endnode





@node "To GEM clipboard"

@toc "Edit menu"

@{U}1.3.16  To GEM clipboard [^G]                          PHOENIX Manager@{u}



If this entry is switched on (shown by a preceding tick mark) then

Cut, Copy and Paste use external storage, else internal memory (RAM).



The external storage corresponds to the CLIPBRD directory, normally

found on drive C:. Its purpose is to allow the exchange of data with

other programs.



@endnode





