@{U}1.7.1  Designer [^F2]                                  PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This menu entry (or the @{"first icon on the desktop" LINK "Schreibtisch des Managers"}) calls the Designer

program, which @{I}must@{i} be located in the same directory as the Manager

program.



If a database is open then this will be passed to the Designer and

loaded into it. This happens via the @{"Program parameters dialog-box" LINK "Dialogbox Programm-Parameter"}.

You can then modify the mask's contents or appearance in any way you

wish.



Before the call all databases will be closed, since they can not be

kept open by the Manager and the Designer simultaneously.  Their data

will be stored in a temporary file with the name MANAGER.TMP, which

will be created in the @{B}Temp directory@{b} (see @{"Configuration dialog-box" LINK "Dialogbox Konfiguration"}).



After returning from the Designer the previously closed databases

will be reopened.



@{I}Note:@{i}

If enough memory is available, the Manager will stay in memory while

the Designer is running. Otherwise the Manager will be quit beforehand

and has to be launched manually again afterwards.



@{I}Further information:@{i} About Designer



@endnode





@node "Reorganisation"

@toc "Options menu"

@{U}1.7.2  Reorganisation [^F3]                            PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This menu entry serves to call the reorganisation module.



The Reorganiser must be called each time new indices are defined

in the @{Designer ignore} when data records have been entered already in the

associated table. This is because then a new index tree has to be

created for them. In such cases an alert message appears.



Additionally the Reorganiser should be called whenever the database

was not closed correctly. This is made known by an alert message when

opening the affected database. This happens for instance in the case

of a power failure, or if the computer crashed or was switched off

before any alterations to the database were saved.



If a database is open when this call is made then the database will

be reorganised. Otherwise the fileselector opens in which a database

has to be selected. In both cases the @{"Reorganise database dialog-box" LINK "Dialogbox Datenbank reorganisieren"}

will appear, in which you may have to enter your name and password to

check that you have the correct access rights to permit this action.

Provided all is well the @{"Reorganisation parameters dialog-box" LINK "Dialogbox Reorganisations-Parameter"} appears.



The reorganisation does not run as a background process.



It is split into five phases:



  1. Creation of a temporary database

  2. Reading the first five data records of the data dictionary

  3. Reading of the whole data dictionary

  4. Writing the data dictionary into the temporary database

  5. Reading and writing the remaining data records



After the reorganisation some statistics about the effect of the

action will be output.



Using the Reorganisation function is also recommended when frequent

alterations have been made to the database (many deletions and

changes). In such cases 'holes' appear in the database in which you

can no longer store any data records. Furthermore all deleted data

records will be stored for the time being. This memory space too will

not be available for new data records. The size of the holes can be

established by invoking the @{"Database info" LINK "Dialogbox Datenbank-Info"} command in the Help menu.



@{I}Note:@{i}

The larger a cache you choose the faster the reorganiser runs.



@{I}Warning!@{i}

After calling the Reorganiser any deleted data records will be lost,

since during reorganisation the wastebin will be cleared.



@endnode





