@node "Import field"

@toc "Options menu (for mask windows)"

@{U}2.3.1  Import field [^I]                               PHOENIX Manager@{u}



Data from external files can be read into a field by activating this

@{"mask window" LINK "Masken-Fenster"} menu entry. Depending on the data type of the field only

certain kinds of data can be imported.



The following table shows the @{"data type" LINK "DESIGNER.HYP/Data types"} and the kind of external file

that can be used:



@{I}Data type      Kind of file @{i}

@Line 1 39 0 0 1

Graphic        GEM and IMG files

BLOB           SAM and any other files

All others     Any ASCII file



So to get graphics into a field, for instance, you have to import the

data from outside into the field. A fileselector-box appears in which

you can choose the desired file.



@{I}Warning!@{i}

Apart from GEM and IMG files, do not import any files with unknown

graphics types into a graphical field, as this could lead to some

unexpected results!



@endnode





@node "Export field"

@toc "Options menu (for mask windows)"

@{U}2.3.2  Export field [^E]                               PHOENIX Manager@{u}



Data from a field can be exported to external files by activating this

@{"mask window" LINK "Masken-Fenster"} menu entry. The data in the field determines the suffix

(extension) that will be suggested in the fileselector's input line.



The following table shows the @{"data type" LINK "DESIGNER.HYP/Data types"} and the kind of external file

that can be used:



@{I}Data type      Suffix of file @{i}

@Line 1 57 0 0 1

Graphic        .GEM or .IMG (depending on field contents)

BLOB           .SAM or .* (dependiong on field conteents)

All others     .*



So to get graphics out of a field, for instance, you have to export

the field. A fileselector-box appears in which you have to input the

external file's name. This allows you to modify graphics outside of

PHOENIX with a graphics program and later reimport them.



@endnode





@node "Display field"

@toc "Options menu (for mask windows)"

@{U}2.3.3  Display field [^O]                              PHOENIX Manager@{u}



On activating this @{"mask window" LINK "Masken-Fenster"} menu entry, an attempt is made to

interpret the contents of a field and to display it. The command can

be selected only when the field is of the data type @{"External file" LINK "DESIGNER.HYP/Data types" 40}

or @{"BLOB" LINK "DESIGNER.HYP/Data types" 72}. With the latter only sound data that had the suffix .SAM

during import can be reproduced. Other interpretations are not yet

available in this version.



A field of the External file data type will contain a filename.

Depending on the suffix an attempt will be made to display the file

in a new window.



The proceedings will be as follows:



@{I}Suffix     Window with @{i}

@Line 1 33 0 0 1

GEM        GEM vector graphic

IMG        GEM bit-image graphic

SAM        Sampled sound data

Any other  ASCII files



If you use external files that contain neither GEM vector graphics,

GEM bit-image files, sound data nor pure ASCII files then this could

lead to unforeseen results.



@endnode





@node "Get filename"

@toc "Options menu (for mask windows)"

@{U}2.3.4  Get filename [^V]                               PHOENIX Manager@{u}



On activating this @{"mask window" LINK "Masken-Fenster"} menu entry, a fileselector-box appears

in which you can select any file you choose. The complete name of the

file (with access path) will be taken over by the field and adapted

to the existing text.



This is particularly useful for fields of the @{"External file" LINK "DESIGNER.HYP/Data types" 40} data

type since then you do not have to input filenames manually.



@endnode





@node "Change mask"

@toc "Options menu (for mask windows)"

@{U}2.3.5  Change mask [^M]                                PHOENIX Manager@{u}



On activating this @{"mask window" LINK "Masken-Fenster"} menu entry, a different mask for the

table of the mask windows can be loaded. The @{"Change mask dialog-box" LINK "Dialogbox Maske wechseln"}

opens.



@endnode





@node "Branch"

@toc "Options menu (for mask windows)"

@{U}2.3.6  Branch [^J]                                     PHOENIX Manager@{u}



On activating this @{"mask window" LINK "Masken-Fenster"} menu entry (or the '~>' icon in the

@{"template window" LINK "Report-Fenster"}), you can branch to another (or the same) table via

an index. The @{"Branch dialog-box" LINK "Dialogbox Verzweigen"} opens.



@endnode





@node "Show popup"

@toc "Options menu (for mask windows)"

@{U}2.3.7  Show popup [^N]                                 PHOENIX Manager@{u}



On activating this @{"mask window" LINK "Masken-Fenster"} menu entry, a popup listbox appears in

the current field under the cursor. Instead of using this command you

can also click with the mouse on the down arrow next to the field, if

there is one.



The values (or items) that appear in the listbox depend on several

factors:



If a value table relationship was defined in @{Designer ignore} for the current

field (see @{"Designer: Value tables" LINK "DESIGNER.HYP/Value tables"}) then all data records of this

value table will be displayed. It will appear sorted if an index was

defined in the value table for the field. Otherwise the values (items)

will appear sequentially.



If no value table was defined, then the listbox displays all values of

the field that are present in the current table. This makes it easy to

check whether a given item exists already, or you can just pick out

one value from the items that are present.



Pressing the [Esc] key, or clicking outside the listbox, retains the

old value in the field and closes the popup.



@endnode





