@node "Batch-Fenster" "Batch window"

@toc "The windows"

@{U}3.1  Batch window                                      PHOENIX Manager@{u}



A batch is a series of commands which can be implemented in the back-

ground (see also Execute).



A batch window can be created by using the NewBatch command in the

Process menu (or its equivalent in the function key bar), as well as

by the Open command as long as a data record in a @{"batch-list window" LINK "Batchliste-Fenster"}

has been selected.



The title line shows the name of the database being used.



The info line shows the current name of the batch. Hence it will be

empty when dealing with a new batch.



Below the info line there are two popup listboxes. These offer the

@{B}Commands@{b} the batch manager understands and the available @{B}Parameters@{b}

for the current command.



The rest of the window serves for defining the batches. This can be

treated as a simple text editor, in which the batch can be entered.



Each command starts on a new line. If a line starts with a ';', then

this line will be regarded as a comment.



The commands and their parameters can be entered in capitals or lower

case - it makes no difference. Alternatively, clicking on any of the

listbox entries will insert the command or parameter at the current

cursor position.



The following commands are defined:



@{I}Command     Meaning @{i}

@Line 1 42 0 0 1

ACCOUNT     Graphical report

CALCULATE   Calculation

CLOSE       Close window

DEFACCOUNT  @{Open ignore} @{"report window" LINK "Bericht-Fenster"}

## Warum gibts keinen Querverweis fuer DEFACCOUNT?

DEFBATCH    @{Open ignore} batch window

DEFCALC     @{Open ignore} @{"calculation window" LINK "Rechnen-Fenster"}

DEFQUERY    @{Open ignore} @{"query window" LINK "Abfrage-Fenster"}

DEFREPORT   @{Open ignore} @{"template window" LINK "Report-Fenster"}

DELETE      Delete

DISK        Output to hard or floppy disk

EDIT        Editing of data records

@{"EXPORT" LINK "EXPORT (batch command)"}      Export

FLUSHKEYS   Write cache

@{"IMPORT" LINK "IMPORT (batch command)"}      Import

LIST        List

LOCKSCREEN  Protect display

MAXIMIZE    Window to full size/restore

MINIMIZE    Iconize window

PRINT       Print

REMOVE      Delete file

REPORT      Output template

SET         Set variables

UNDELETE    Undelete/restore data records



The commands may require parameters. These always follow the command

itself. If no parameters are specified, then default values will be

used.



The commands may be assigned the following parameters:



@{I}Command     Parameter @{i}

@Line 1 71 0 0 1

ACCOUNT     <TABLE> <INDEX> <DIR> <QUERY> <EXCLUSIVE> @{<MINIMIZE ignore}> <NAME>

            <DEVICE> <COPIES>

CALCULATE   <TABLE> <QUERY> <INDEX> <DIR> @{<MINIMIZE ignore}> <NAME> <EXCLUSIVE>

CLOSE

DEFACCOUNT  <NAME>

DEFBATCH    <NAME> <FACENAME> <FONTSIZE> <COLOR>

DEFCALC     <TABLE> <NAME> <FACENAME> <FONTSIZE> <COLOR>

DEFQUERY    <TABLE> <NAME>

DEFREPORT   <TABLE> <NAME> <FACENAME> <FONTSIZE> <COLOR>

DELETE      <TABLE> <QUERY> <INDEX> <DIR> @{<MINIMIZE ignore}> <EXCLUSIVE>

DISK        <TABLE> <QUERY> <INDEX> <DIR> @{<MINIMIZE ignore}> <FILE> <LAY>

            <EXCLUSIVE>

EDIT        <TABLE> <QUERY> <INDEX> <DIR> <NAME> <SIZE>

@{"EXPORT" LINK "EXPORT (batch command)"}      <TABLE> <QUERY> <INDEX> <DIR> @{<MINIMIZE ignore}> <FILE> <IMP>

            <EXCLUSIVE>

FLUSHKEYS

@{"IMPORT" LINK "IMPORT (batch command)"}      <TABLE> <QUERY> @{<MINIMIZE ignore}> <FILE> <IMP> <EXCLUSIVE>

LIST        <TABLE> <QUERY> <INDEX> <DIR> @{<MINIMIZE ignore}> <FACENAME>

            <FONTSIZE> <COLOR> <SIZE>

LOCKSCREEN

MAXIMIZE

MINIMIZE

PRINT       <TABLE> <QUERY> <INDEX> <DIR> @{<MINIMIZE ignore}> <PRN> <PRT>

            <LAY> <EXCLUSIVE>

REMOVE      <FILE>

REPORT      <TABLE> <QUERY> <INDEX> <DIR> @{<MINIMIZE ignore}> <DEVICE>

            <FILE> <PRN> <PRT> <COPIES> <NAME> <EXCLUSIVE>

SET         <TABLE> <INDEX> <DIR> <FACENAME> <FONTSIZE> <COLOR>

UNDELETE    <EXCLUSIVE>



If a query is specified (with the parameter QUERY), then the parame-

ters TABLE, INDEX and DIR lose their meaning, and will be ignored.



The parameters are always specified by the syntax PARAMETER=VALUE,

where the word PARAMETER is replaced by the corresponding parameter

and VALUE by the desired value.



The following syntax applies for the parameters:



@line 9 0 17

@line 22 0 17

@line 65 0 17

@line 9 56 0

         @{I}Parameter    Syntax @{i}

@line 9 56 0

         <TABLE>      TABLE=<Name>|<Number>

@line 9 56 0

         <INDEX>      INDEX=<Name>|<Number>

@line 9 56 0

         <DIR>        DIR=ASC|DESC

@line 9 56 0

         <QUERY>      QUERY="<Queryname>"

@line 9 56 0

         <EXCLUSIVE>  EXCLUSIVE=TRUE|FALSE

@line 9 56 0

         @{<MINIMIZE ignore}>   @{<MINIMIZE ignore}>=TRUE|FALSE

@line 9 56 0

         <FACENAME>   FACENAME="<Name of a font>"

@line 9 56 0

         <FILE>       FILE="<Filename>"

@line 9 56 0

         <NAME>       NAME="<Objectname>"

@line 9 56 0

         <DEVICE>     DEVICE=SCREEN|@{"DISK" ignore}|PRINTER

@line 9 56 0

         <FONTSIZE>   FONTSIZE=<Number>

@line 9 56 0

         <SIZE>       SIZE=<Number>,<Number>,<Number>,<Number>

@line 9 56 0

         <COLOR>      COLOR=<No. of the font colour>

@line 9 56 0

         <IMP>        IMP="<Filename>"

@line 9 56 0

         <LAY>        LAY="<Filename>"

@line 9 56 0

         <PRN>        PRN="<Filename>"

@line 9 56 0



Here the character '|' means OR, and one of its listed options @{I}has@{i}

to be used.



The parameter values have the following meaning:



@{I}Param. value   Meaning @{i}

@Line 1 61 0 0 1

<Name>         Identifier of a table or an index.

<Number>       A positive number or the number of a table or

               of an index. The numbering starts with 0.

<Queryname>    Name of a query.

<Filename>     Name of an external file.

<Objectname>   Name of an object, which can be a calculation,

               a template, a batch, a query or a mask.

ASC            Ascending

DESC           Descending

TRUE           True (switched on)

FALSE          False (switched off)

SCREEN         Monitor screen

@{DISK ignore}           Hard or floppy disk

PRINTER        Printer



If parameters are omitted then default values will be substituted.

For filenames you will be asked first for the file, with devices for

the screen, file or printer.



 <EXCLUSIVE>  means that a process is run exclusively.



 @{<MINIMIZE ignore}>   means that a process or a @{"table window" LINK "Tabellen-Fenster"} is stored

              immediately after creation as an icon.



 <DEVICE>     means the output device for the template.



 <FONTSIZE>   means the height of the font for a table window

              (see @{"Font dialog-box" LINK "Dialogbox Schriftart"}).



 <SIZE>       is the size of a table window. The four values specify

              the X- and Y-coordinates as well as width and height of

              the window. The first two values are multiplied by the

              width or height respectively of the system font, the

              two latter ones give the size in characters and lines.

              The actual size is dependent of the selected font.



The four values that can be set with the SET command are variables

that are initialised at the start of a batch-run:



 TABLE:     First table

 INDEX:     First index

 DIR:       ASC

 FONTSIZE:  System font



These variables are independent of the settings made by the user in

the @{"database toolbox" LINK "Schreibtisch des Managers" "Database toolbox"}. The values will be used whenever a command has

not included specifications of table, index, direction or font size.



@{U}Activating the listbox from the keybard@{u}

- [Shift]+[F3] activates the command listbox

- [Shift]+[F4] activates the parameter listbox



A batch is activated by the command Execute.



@index "AUTOEXEC"

Furthermore, the batch with the name AUTOEXEC, if it exists, will be

executed automatically on opening a database. With this it is simple

to store default settings on the desktop.

Pressing one of the [Shift] keys while opening a database will prevent

the execution of the AUTOEXEC batch.



@endnode





@node "ACCOUNT"

@toc "Batch-Fenster"

@{U}3.1.1  ACCOUNT                                         PHOENIX Manager@{u}



ACCOUNT <TABLE> <INDEX> <DIR> <QUERY> <EXCLUSIVE> @{<MINIMIZE ignore}> <NAME>

<DEVICE> <COPIES>



This executes a report.



@{I}Example:@{i}

ACCOUNT TABLE=INVOICE NAME=INVOICE COPIES=2



@endnode





@node "CALCULATE"

@toc "Batch-Fenster"

@{U}3.1.2  CALCULATE                                       PHOENIX Manager@{u}



CALCULATE <TABLE> <QUERY> <INDEX> <DIR> @{<MINIMIZE ignore}> <NAME> <EXCLUSIVE>



The batch function CALCULATE executes a calculation. It has the same

effect as the Process/Execute menu entry with an opened calculation

window. This calculation must have been defined previously and saved

in the calculation-list (see @{"calculation window" LINK "Rechnen-Fenster"}).

As parameters one has to pass at least the name of the calculation

in the parameter field NAME= and the table on which the calculation

is to be performed in the parameter field TABLE=.



@{I}Example:@{i}

CALCULATE TABLE=INVOICES NAME="SUM" MINIMIZE=TRUE



@endnode





@node "CLOSE"

@toc "Batch-Fenster"

@{U}3.1.3  CLOSE                                           PHOENIX Manager@{u}



The topped window will be closed. The command corresponds to the

File/Close menu entry.



@{I}Example:@{i}

CLOSE



@endnode



@node "DEFBATCH"

@toc "Batch-Fenster"

@{U}3.1.4  DEFBATCH                                        PHOENIX Manager@{u}



DEFBATCH <NAME> <FACENAME> <FONTSIZE> <COLOR>



This command opens a @{"batch window" LINK "Batch-Fenster"} so that you can define a new batch

or modify an existing one.



@{I}Example:@{i}

DEFBATCH NAME="ADRESSES" FACENAME="CHICAGO" FONTSIZE=10



@endnode





@node "DEFCALC"

@toc "Batch-Fenster"

@{U}3.1.5  DEFCALC                                         PHOENIX Manager@{u}



DEFCALC <TABLE> <NAME> <FACENAME> <FONTSIZE> <COLOR>



This batch command opens a @{"calculation window" LINK "Rechnen-Fenster"}.



@{I}Example:@{i}

DEFCALC



@endnode





@node "DEFQUERY"

@toc "Batch-Fenster"

@{U}3.1.6  DEFQUERY                                        PHOENIX Manager@{u}



DEFQUERY <TABLE> <NAME>



This command opens a @{"query window" LINK "Abfrage-Fenster"} and permits the definition or

modification of a query.



@{I}Example:@{i}

DEFQUERY TABLE=ADDRESSES NAME="PRIVATE"



@endnode





@node "DEFREPORT"

@toc "Batch-Fenster"

@{U}3.1.7  DEFREPORT                                       PHOENIX Manager@{u}



DEFREPORT <TABLE> <NAME> <FACENAME> <FONTSIZE> <COLOR>



This command opens a @{"template window" LINK "Report-Fenster"} and permits inputting a template.



@{I}Example:@{i}

DEFREPORT TABLE=ADDRESSES NAME="ADDRESSLABELS"



@endnode





@node "DELETE"

@toc "Batch-Fenster"

@{U}3.1.8  DELETE                                          PHOENIX Manager@{u}



DELETE <TABLE> <QUERY> <INDEX> <DIR> @{<MINIMIZE ignore}> <EXCLUSIVE>



The batch command DELETE is used for deleting data records. It serves

the same purpose as the Edit/Delete main menu entry, or the dragging

of data records and @{"table icons" LINK "Tabellen-Sinnbild"} to the wastebin.



The data records to be deleted are specified via the parameters. So

if you specify the parameter TABLE= , the whole table will be deleted

(so be careful!) With the parameter QUERY one can specify the name of

a query that selects the data records to be deleted.



@{I}Example:@{i}

DELETE TABLE=CLIENTS deletes all data records of the table CLIENTS.



@endnode





@node "DISK"

@toc "Batch-Fenster"

@{U}3.1.9  DISK                                            PHOENIX Manager@{u}



DISK <TABLE> <QUERY> <INDEX> <DIR> @{<MINIMIZE ignore}> <FILE> <LAY> <EXCLUSIVE>



This batch command is used for outputting table lists to a file.

It is comparable to the File/Disk output entry of the main menu.



As parameters you have to pass at least the name of the table to be

exported (TABLE=) or a query for selecting the data (QUERY=) and the

name of the output file (FILE=). Should the output be in a given

format (page length, headers/footers...), then the output format can

be set via the Parameters/@{"Page format dialog-box" LINK "Dialogbox Seitenformat"} and saved in the

parameters file with the suffix .LAY. During execution of the batch

command this file can be specified via the parameter LAY= and then

loaded.



@{I}Example:@{i}

DISK QUERY="@{Open ignore} invoice" FILE="OPEN.DAT" LAY="RE_LISTE.LAY"



@endnode





@node "EDIT"

@toc "Batch-Fenster"

@{U}3.1.10  EDIT                                           PHOENIX Manager@{u}



EDIT <TABLE> <QUERY> <INDEX> <DIR> <NAME> <SIZE>



The batch command EDIT brins the input mask of the table specified by

TABLE= to the screen. If only a selection of data records in the input

mask are to be modified, then these can be selected by a query

specified by QUERY=. If the parameter INDEX= is used to specify an

index field, then the data records will displayed in the input mask

sorted according to this index, and one can search and browse in the

mask. If several masks were defined for a table and a different mask

to the standard one is to be displayed, then specify the name of this

mask in the parameter field NAME=.



@{I}Example:@{i}

EDIT TABLE=CLIENTS INDEX=ClientNo DIR=DESC NAME="MaskTwo"



(Meaning: For the table @{B}CLIENTS@{b} the input mask with the name @{B}MaskTwo@{b}

will be displayed; the data records will be sorted in descending order

by the @{B}ClientNo@{b} index field.)



@endnode





@node "EXPORT (batch command)"

@toc "Batch-Fenster"

@{U}3.1.11  EXPORT (batch command)                         PHOENIX Manager@{u}



@{EXPORT ignore} <TABLE> <QUERY> <INDEX> <DIR> @{<MINIMIZE ignore}> <FILE> <IMP>

<EXCLUSIVE>



With the batch command @{EXPORT ignore} one can export data records. It is

comparable to the File/Export entry of the main menu. You can export

a complete table (by specifying the parameter TABLE=), or just a

selection of data records that are determined by a query in the

QUERY= parameter. The name of the export file is set by the parameter

field FILE=. After IMP= you can specify a parameter file with export

parameters.



@{I}Example:@{i}

@{EXPORT ignore} TABLE=ADDRESSES INDEX=Name FILE="ADR.ASC" IMP="PORTFOL.IMP"



@endnode





@node "FLUSHKEYS"

@toc "Batch-Fenster"

@{U}3.1.12  FLUSHKEYS                                      PHOENIX Manager@{u}



The index key file and/or the data file will be written. This command

is only useful if @{B}Write index@{b} or @{B}Write data@{b} were switched off in the

@{"Open database dialog-box" LINK "Dialogbox Datenbank îffnen"}, since otherwise the index file is updated

anyhow at each saving process.



@endnode





@node "IMPORT (batch command)"

@toc "Batch-Fenster"

@{U}3.1.13  IMPORT (batch command)                         PHOENIX Manager@{u}



@{IMPORT ignore} <TABLE> <QUERY> @{<MINIMIZE ignore}> <FILE> <IMP> <EXCLUSIVE>



Data records will be imported into the table TABLE=. The import file

is FILE=. Should the required import parameters differ from the set

default parameters, then as for @{"EXPORT" LINK "EXPORT (batch command)"} you can use IMP= to specify a

file with import parameters.



@{I}Example:@{i}

@{IMPORT ignore} TABLE=ADDRESSES FILE="ADR.ASC" IMP="PORTFOL.IMP"



@endnode





@node "LIST"

@toc "Batch-Fenster"

@{U}3.1.14  LIST                                           PHOENIX Manager@{u}



LIST <TABLE> <QUERY> <INDEX> <DIR> @{<MINIMIZE ignore}> <FACENAME> <FONTSIZE>

<COLOR> <SIZE>



Creates a @{"table window" LINK "Tabellen-Fenster"} on the screen and so has the same effect as a

double-click on a table or index name in the @{"database toolbox" LINK "Schreibtisch des Managers" "Database toolbox"}. The

relevant table can be determined via the parameter TABLE=. Should a

query be performed, then just give the name of the query with the

parameter field QUERY=. With FONTSIZE= you can set the character size

and with SIZE= the size of the output window. @{MINIMIZE ignore}=TRUE will

display the table window as an icon.



@{I}Example:@{i}

LIST QUERY="@{Open ignore} invoices" @{MINIMIZE ignore}=TRUE FONTSIZE=9



@endnode





@node "LOCKSCREEN"

@toc "Batch-Fenster"

@{U}3.1.15  LOCKSCREEN                                     PHOENIX Manager@{u}



Protects the screen display (see also Options/Protect display).

This function is available only if passwords were assigned to the

database. A window covering the whole screen appears, which will

vanish only when the correct password is input.



@{I}Example:@{i}

LOCKSCREEN



@endnode





@node "MAXIMIZE"

@toc "Batch-Fenster"

@{U}3.1.16  MAXIMIZE                                       PHOENIX Manager@{u}



The topped window will be enlarged to fill the screen, or, if it fills

it already, restored to its original size. This command has the same

effect as a mouse-click on the 'Fuller' box at the top right corner of

a window.



@{I}Example:@{i}

MAXIMIZE



@endnode





@node "MINIMIZE"

@toc "Batch-Fenster"

@{U}3.1.17  MINIMIZE                                       PHOENIX Manager@{u}



The topped window will be displayed as an icon.



@endnode





@node "PRINT"

@toc "Batch-Fenster"

@{U}3.1.18  PRINT                                          PHOENIX Manager@{u}



PRINT <TABLE> <QUERY> <INDEX> <DIR> @{<MINIMIZE ignore}> <PRN> <PRT> <LAY>

<EXCLUSIVE>



Outputs data records in list form to the printer. With TABLE= a

complete table will be output, with QUERY= you can make a data

selection. The parameter PRN= can be assigned the name of a printer

parameter file. The setting of printer parameters is explained in

the @{"Printer parameters" LINK "Dialogbox Drucker-Parameter"} section. PRT= can be used if output is to be

to a different printer from that installed as a default. Just put the

name of the driver file here. After executing the template, the

default driver will be reloaded.



@{I}Example:@{i}

PRINT TABLE=ADDRESSES INDEX=Name PRN="BOLD.PRN" PRT="EPSONFX.PRT"



@endnode





@node "REMOVE"

@toc "Batch-Fenster"

@{U}3.1.19  REMOVE                                         PHOENIX Manager@{u}



REMOVE <FILE>



The function REMOVE deletes the file secified by FILE=.



@{I}Example:@{i}

REMOVE FILE="K:\CLIENTS\CLIENTS.TMP"



deletes the file CLIENTS.TMP in the K:\CLIENTS\ directory.



@endnode





@node "REPORT"

@toc "Batch-Fenster"

@{U}3.1.20  REPORT                                         PHOENIX Manager@{u}



REPORT <TABLE> <QUERY> <INDEX> <DIR> @{<MINIMIZE ignore}> <DEVICE> <FILE> <PRN>

<PRT> <COPIES> <NAME> <EXCLUSIVE>



The function REPORT is used within a batch to execute a template.

This template must have been defined beforehand and saved with the

database.  TABLE= or QUERY= specify the data records to be output.

DEVICE= sets the output device. Should the output be to a file

(DEVICE=DISK), you have to use the parameter FILE= to specify the

name of the output file. NAME= contains the name of the template.



@{I}Example:@{i}

REPORT QUERY="Open_invoices" NAME="Reminder" DEVICE=DISK

FILE="D:\PHOENIX\CLIENTS\REMINDER.TXT" EXCLUSIVE=TRUE



@endnode





@node "SET"

@toc "Batch-Fenster"

@{U}3.1.21  SET                                            PHOENIX Manager@{u}



SET <TABLE> <INDEX> <DIR> <FACENAME> <FONTSIZE> <COLOR>



With the batch function SET you can set some batch parameters to be

used when the batch is executed. You will then not have to specify

these parameters again when calling the batch commands.



@{I}Example:@{i}

SET TABLE=CLIENTS INDEX=ClientNo DIR=DESC FONTSIZE=10



@endnode





@node "UNDELETE"

@toc "Batch-Fenster"

@{U}3.1.22  UNDELETE                                       PHOENIX Manager@{u}



UNDELETE <EXCLUSIVE>



Restores previously deleted data records (e.g. with DELETE) into the

correct tables.



This function corresponds to the use of the Edit/Paste command of

the main menu with the @{"Wastebin icon" LINK "Papierkorb-Sinnbild"} selected.



@endnode





@node "Batchliste-Fenster" "Batch-list window"

@toc "The windows"

@{U}3.2  Batch-list window [F9]                           PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This is a @{"table window" LINK "Tabellen-Fenster"} displaying the names of the batches. The window

has additional properties.



With a data record selected in this window, the following actions can

be performed:

- Left double-click: Performing the Open command

- Right double-click: Performing the Execute command



Executing the Open command does not open a @{"mask window" LINK "Masken-Fenster"} as with normal

table windows, but a @{"batch window" LINK "Batch-Fenster"} instead. This window then holds the

contents of the previously selected data record, allowing batches that

have been saved earlier to be modified.



However, if you do want to define a template via a normal mask window

(though this will not be necessary as a rule), then after making the

selection you can call the Edit data command to make a mask appear.



@endnode





@node "Rechnen-Fenster" "Calculation window"

@toc "The windows"

@autorefoff

@{U}3.3  Calculation window                                PHOENIX Manager@{u}

@autorefon



A calculation window can be created by using the New@{Calculation ignore}

command in the Process menu (or its equivalent in the function key

bar), or by using the Open command provided that a data record in a

calculation-list is selected during this.



The window serves for the definition of a calculation and is built up

in a similar way to a @{"template window" LINK "Report-Fenster"}. The title line of the window

shows the table for which the calculation is to be created.



When the New@{Calculation ignore} command in the Process menu is activated,

the table currently selected in the @{"database toolbox" LINK "Schreibtisch des Managers" "Database toolbox"} will be used.



## Addiert/Erweitert

You can also open a calculation window for an existing entry in a

@{"calculation-list window" LINK "Rechnenliste-Fenster"} by double-clicking on an entry or using the

Open command while an item in this list is selected; this too will

show the currently selected table from the database toolbox in the

@{B}Table@{b} listbox, and it is up to you to select the correct name from

the drop-down list. If the calculation was saved previously, the

info line above will contain the name of the calculation.



In the area below this are four popup listboxes. They contain all the

tables, fields and indices as well as all the operators and reserved

designators that may be used in a calculation. The contents of the

@{B}Field@{b} and @{B}Index@{b} listboxes will change if another @{B}Table@{b} is selected.

## Erweitert



@{U}The listbox may be operated from the keyboard:@{u}

- [Shift]+[F3] drops down the @{B}Table@{b} listbox

- [Shift]+[F4] drops down the @{B}Field@{b} listbox

- [Shift]+[F5] drops down the @{B}Index@{b} listbox

- [Shift]+[F6] drops down the @{B}Op@{b}erators listbox

You can then use the up/down arrow keys to select one of the items

in the list.



## Erweitert

The lower part of the window is the area where you can define your

calculation. You can either type in the definition, or use the items

in the @{B}Field@{b}, @{B}Index@{b} and @{B}Op@{b}erator listboxes: Pressing [Return] or

[Enter] inserts the item selected in the listbox at the cursor

position.



To use several calculation commands in a definition, separate the

individual assignments with a semicolon (;).



@{I}Example:@{i}

Buy_date = SYSDATE;

Total_cost = Number * Unit_price;



If one of the commands Execute, Allocate calculation, Save or Save as

is performed then the calculation will be checked, and if it is not

in order you will be informed of the error and its position by an

alert box.



To save your calculation definition under a name of your choice, use

the Save as menu command to open the @{"Save calculation as dialog-box" LINK "Dialogbox Rechnen sichern als"}.

Only correct definitions can be saved.



@{U}Operators and Designators@{u}



The following table lists all operators and designators:



@{I}Operator/Designator  Meaning @{i}

