@{I}Tip:@{i}

The LAST designator provides an excellent way of automating the

progressive numbering of client numbers, for instance.



With the calculation:



Clientnumber = LAST (Clientnumber) + 1;



you will always get the first free client number that has not been

used yet, even if some client numbers have been deleted meanwhile.



@{U}Data types@{u}

Every field has a given data type (Text, Number, Long, Date etc.).

For more details, see @{"Data types" LINK "DESIGNER.HYP/Data types"} in the @{Designer ignore} Help pages.



Depending on the data type, not every assignment and combination of

fields is permitted. Thus, for instance, you can not add a Time field

to a Floating-point field. Furthermore, the designator SYSDATE can

be used only in connection with Date fields, the designator SYSTIME

only in connection with Time fields and the designator SYSTIMESTAMP

only in connection with fields of the TIMESTAMP type.

All numbers (Number, Long, Floating-point) that appear in a calcuation

are first converted internally to floating-point numbers and only then

will the calculation be performed.

During the assignment to a field it will then be converted back to a

suitable type.



@{U}Text fields and fields of the External file type@{u}

With Text and @{"External file" LINK "DESIGNER.HYP/Data types" 40} fields, only the '+' operator may be used.

An addition of two texts means a concatenation of both character-

strings:

PLZ_Town = PLZ + " " + Town gives the value '69126 Heidelberg' if the

field 'PLZ' contains the mumber 69126 and the field 'Town' the value

Heidelberg.



To replace a character-string by another one you can use the REPLACE

command.



@{I}Examples:@{i}

a)

Name = REPLACE (Name, "Ñ", "ae");



replaces every 'Ñ' by 'ae' in the field 'Name'.



b)

NameWithDots = REPLACE (Forename : 20, ' ', '.');



fills up the forename to 20 places with dots.



c)

Name = SUBSTR (Text, 3, 4);



assigns to the field 'Name' from the third character of Text onwards

four further characters.



d)

VAR i;

i = 1;

WHILE (i <= 10) DO

FIELD ("Name" + i) = ";



sets all fields 'Name1' etc. to 'Name10' to empty.



@{U}Date, Time and Timestamp fields@{u}

For fields of this type you can apply only addition or subtraction.

The fields 'Guaranteed_to' and 'Purchased' are of the type Date.



The calculation



Guaranteed_to = Purchased;

MONTH (Guaranteed_to) = MONTH (Guaranteed_to) + 6;



adds 6 months to the field 'Guaranteed_to'. Before this the field

'Guaranteed_to' has to be filled with the value of the field

'Purchased'!



The subtraction of two Date fields returns the number of days between

the two dates. Leap years are taken into account. Thus



Used = SYSDATE - Purchased;



gives the number of days elapsed since the purchase date. The field

'Used' here is of the type Number, Long or Floating-point.



To a Time field one can only sensibly add another time value. The

subtraction of two time values returns a time interval in the format

HHMMSSmmmmmm (the 'm' represents microseconds).



Time constants can be added to or subtracted from Time fields as

follows: 'End_max' and 'Start_time' are two fields of the type TIME:



End_max = Start_time + TIME (00:13:45);



The field 'End_max' is assigned the value 'Start_time' increased by

13 minutes and 45 seconds.



To a field of the type TIMESTAMP you can add Date and Time fields.

The subtraction of two TIMESTAMP values returns a duration in the

format



DDMMYYYYHHMMSSmmmmmm (Day,Month,Year,Hour,Minute,Second,Microsecond).



@{I}Examples:@{i}

Seconds = SECOND (Time) + MINUTE (Time) * 60 + HOUR (Time) * 3600;



calculates the number of seconds from the field 'Time' and assigns

these to the field 'Seconds'.



Days = SYSDATE - DATE (17.3.1991);



calculates the days between the current date and the constant

date 17.3.1991. The constant date must be specified in the default

format. This can be changed in @{Designer ignore} (see the @{"Format command" LINK "DESIGNER.HYP/Dialogbox Format"} in

@{Designer ignore}).



@endnode





@node "Rechnenliste-Fenster" "Calculation-list window"

@toc "The windows"

@autorefoff

@{U}3.4  Calculation-list window [F8]                     PHOENIX Manager@{u}

@autorefon



This window is a normal @{"table window" LINK "Tabellen-Fenster"}. It displays the table names for

which a calculation was defined, and the names of the calculations.

The third column of the table contains the text of the calculation.



In contrast to a normal table, this window has additional properties.

If a data record in this window is selected then the following actions

can be performed:

- Left double-click: Call of the Open command

- Right double-click: Call of the Execute command

- @{B}Allocate calculation@{b} command: Assigns the calculation to the current

  table



When executing the Open command, instead of opening a mask window as

with normal table windows, a @{"calculation window" LINK "Rechnen-Fenster"} will be opened. This

displays the previously selected data record. In it, previously saved

calculations can be modified. How a valculation window is used is

described in the @{"Calculation window" LINK "Rechnen-Fenster"} section.



If you want to modify a calculation definition via a normal mask

window, then after selecting an entry, the Edit data command of the

Edit menu can be activated, which makes a mask appear.



## Erweitert

This will be the mask SYSTEM.Rechnungen (= SYSTEM.Calculations). In

this calculation-list window you can input a calculation directly in

the large @{B}Text@{b} field; the contents scroll when you reach the right

border. The @{B}Name@{b} field can be edited freely, so that you can alter

the name of the calculation subsequently.

For executing the calculation, however, it has to be saved first (with

the @{Save ignore} button [DB] in the icon bar or the @{B}Record/@{Save ignore}@{b} menu entry of

the mask window), then selected in the calculation-list and the Execute

command called. The @{B}Code@{b} and @{B}Flags@{b} fields are only used internally

and should not be altered.



The only advantage of this type of definition is that a Text field can

be imported and exported in a mask window. This makes it possible to

adopt a calculation from an external text editor by placing the cursor

in the @{B}Text@{b} field and using the Import field command.



@endnode





@node "Klemmbrett-Fenster" "Clipboard window"

@toc "The windows"

@{U}3.5  Clipboard window                                  PHOENIX Manager@{u}



@{I}The following only applies if CLIPBRD.ACC is installed on the system!@{i}



The clipboard window appears by double-clicking on the @{"Clipboard icon" LINK "Klemmbrett-Sinnbild"}.

It displays the contents of the GEM clipboard.



An item in the clipboard can be opened by double-clicking on it.



@endnode





@node "Editor-Fenster" "Editor window"

@toc "The windows"

@{U}3.6  Editor window                                     PHOENIX Manager@{u}



An editor window is opened when texts are to be displayed on-screen.

It can be activated by double-clicking the Drive icon on the desktop.

A fileselector-box opens in which you have to select the file

containing the text. If there is none, create an empty file CACHE.IDX

in your TMP directory and use that.



In the editor window you can modify the text. The cursor can be posi-

tioned with the mouse. Marking (highlighting) is not yet possible in

this version, however. A line can be deleted by pressing both the

[Control] and [@{Delete ignore}] keys together. For keyboard control, the same

applies as for a text object in the @{"mask window" LINK "Masken-Fenster" 121}.



@endnode





@node "Masken-Fenster" "Mask window"

@toc "The windows"

@xref "Change mask"

@{U}3.7  Mask window                                       PHOENIX Manager@{u}



A mask window is created with the Edit data command of the Edit menu

(or its equivalent in the function key bar on the desktop).



If there is no item selected, a mask for the current table from the

@{"database toolbox" LINK "Schreibtisch des Managers" "Database toolbox"} appears. Otherwise a mask for the table to which

the item belongs appears.



The first data record of the current sorting order from the database

toolbox is displayed automatically. If the table is empty, then an

empty mask appears.



The mask of the table that was defined first in @{Designer ignore} will be used

in each case. But you can also change the mask to suit your wishes

(see Change mask command).



A mask window is divided into four areas:

@autorefoff

- Title line

- Menu-bar, and icon bar buttons (at top edge of window)

- Info line

- Working area



@{U}Title line@{u}

@autorefon

The title line of the window displays the database and table names,

separated by a point.



@{U}Menu-bar, and icon bar buttons@{u}

The menu-bar, as well as the icon bar buttons that duplicate some of

the menu entries, can be serviced with either the left or right mouse

button. When you click on a menu, it drops down; then this menu can be

used in the same way as the main menu at the top edge of the screen.



In the icon bar below the info line you can alter the index key in

the listbox and the sorting direction with the @{B}+/-@{b} buttons.

In addition there are icon buttons which perform commands in the mask

window.

