@{U}Dragging from table windows@{u}

Data records from a @{"table window" LINK "Tabellen-Fenster"} can be dragged to a mask window. The

effect depends on whether the table and mask windows originated from

the same table or not:



   ˘ From same table:

     The data record from the table window will be copied to the mask

     window and displayed in it.



   ˘ From a table window that was a value table for the mask:

     If the data record comes from the table window of a value table

     of the mask window, then all values will be adopted automatically

     that were set in the definition in @{"Designer" LINK "DESIGNER.HYP/Value tables"}. In this way you can

     put the postcode and town from a value table directly into the

     mask, for instance.



     If a value table is used in several fields of the same mask, then

     the mouse cursor must be positioned exactly on the corresponding

     field of the mask that is to be filled from the value table.



@endnode





@node "Pixelgrafik-Fenster" "Pixel graphics window"

@toc "The windows"

@{U}3.8  Pixel graphics window                             PHOENIX Manager@{u}



The window displays images in the .IMG bit image file format. For this

you can also call the Info command.



@endnode





@node "Vorschau-Fenster" "Preview window"

@toc "The windows"

@{U}3.9  Preview window                                    PHOENIX Manager@{u}



The preview window opens when you execute a report.



Here you can obtain an overview of the report before committing it

finally to paper.



To print it out you now need to activate File/Print or click on the

Printer icon in Manager's icon bar.



The display scale of the preview can be chosen in a popup.

Alternatively, a left-click in the window enlarges the scale by one

step, while a right-click reduces it by a similar amount.



The black-and-white button produces a preview of how the printout

would look on a black-and-white printer. This is useful if you have

used colours in the report but now have to print it out on a mono

laser or inkjet printer.



With the sideways arrow buttons you can browse through the report

preview page by page, or jump to the start or end.



@endnode





@node "Prozeû-Fenster" "Process window"

@toc "The windows"

@{U}3.10  Process window                                   PHOENIX Manager@{u}



The process window window opens when a process is being executed. Its

title line shows what kind of action is being performed at the time.



The first line in the window shows the path and file being written to.

If it concerns the printer, then the name of the interface port will

be displayed. For some processes it may be left empty.



The second line shows the database and the table taking part in the

action.



The third line - if present - shows the columns used for producing

the sorted output and the sorting order.



@{U}Time information:@{u}



 @{B}Running@{b} shows how long the process has been running already

     (hours:minutes:seconds).

 @{B}Remaining@{b} shows approximately how much longer the process will run

     (hours:minutes:seconds).

 @{B}Pause@{b} serves to block the process for an indefinite time. The

     switch can not be activated when the process is blocked by the

     Manager.

 @{B}Exclusive@{b} is a switch whose activation allocates the complete CPU

     calculation time to the process; all other processes are paused.

     This state of affairs is terminated by clicking with either mouse

     button on the checkbox.



 @{B}Data record@{b} shows which data record the processing has reached. If

     the running process is the spooler, then instead of 'Data record'

     the word 'Bytes' will be displayed.



Below the data record field is a bar which shows the progress of the

action visually.

The bar wanders from left to right and gives a rough overview how far

processing has progressed. Above the bar are the two limiting values.

At the left is a 0, at the right the maximum number of data records

in the current table or the number of bytes when dealing with the

spooler. During importing the upper limit floats.



@autorefoff

 @{B}Iconize@{b} serves to shrink the process to a minimum size, so that it

@autorefon

     does not require so much space on the desktop (see @{"Process icon" LINK "Prozeû-Sinnbild"}).



@{I}Note:@{i}

If a process for a database is running, then this database can not be

closed. Should you want to do this nevertheless, then all processes

that pertain to this database must be aborted. For the same reason it

is not possible to terminate the program, since this closes all the

databases. The same applies for calling up other programs, since this

might mean quitting the Manager for the time being.



A process can be aborted also by pressing the [Esc] or [@{Undo ignore}] key.



@endnode





@node "Eigenschaften-Fenster" "Properties window"

@toc "The windows"

@xref "The properties"

@{U}3.11  Properties window                                PHOENIX Manager@{u}



A properties window opens when you double-click on an item or area

(such as the headers, footers or detail areas, or the rulers) in a

@{"report window" LINK "Bericht-Fenster"}. Depending on the what you have clicked on, the main

part of the window displays various @{"properties" LINK "The properties"} or attributes of the

item or area that may be altered here, with their current status.



Click on the property you want to change to select it. The current

value appears in the long field above the listed properties, followed

by one of two kinds of cursor: If this is a solid rectangle, then you

can type in a new value into the field and press [Return] to insert it

in the table and modify the item in the report. Note that you @{I}must@{i}

use a comma instead of a decimal point as a separator for numbers

with decimal places.



If the cursor is a hollow rectangle, the field turns into a listbox

and clicking on the small arrow box at far right drops down a list of

options from which you can make your selection. (An exception is the

@{B}@{Font ignore}@{b} entry, where the box shows three dots and clicking on it opens

the @{"Font dialog-box" LINK "Dialogbox Schriftart"} where you can choose both the type and size of

font, as well as any font attributes). A click on one of the listbox

entries will insert it in the relevant field of the @{"Properties" LINK "The properties"} list

and it will be applied to the item or area in the report.



@endnode





@node "Abfrage-Fenster" "Query window"

@toc "The windows"

@xref "Dialogbox Sortierung" "Sorting dialog-box"

@{U}3.12  Query window                                     PHOENIX Manager@{u}



A query window can be created by using the NewQuery command in the

Process menu (or its equivalent in the function key bar), or by the

Open command as long as a data record in a @{"query-list window" LINK "Abfrageliste-Fenster"} has

been selected.



The window serves to put a query to a database without having to learn

a query language first. For this reason such a query is also called

QBE, meaning query By example.



The window's title line shows the name of the database and the name

of the table.



@autorefoff

The info line shows the name of the current query. Hence it will be

empty when dealing with a new query.

@autorefon



The icon bar can be used to call the change sorting order (@{B}+/-@{b}) and

Complement columns (crossed<->uncrossed box)  functions.



Complementing changes the columns that are to be output at a query,

namely:

- Selected columns will be deselected

- Deselected columns will be selected



@{I}Tip:@{i}

If the command is called accidentally, then a repeat call can anul

its effect and restore the original selection.



The sorting can be specified by up to 16 steps. More about this in

the @{"Sorting dialog-box" LINK "Dialogbox Sortierung"}.



The column names lie below the info line. Under each column name there

is a checkbox switch indicating whether the column is to be output or

not. In addition, next to the switch it is noted whether this field is

to be taken account of during sorting or not.



Below this there are 16 lines which are to take the conditions.



@{U}Selection of columns (fields)@{u}

Selection of the columns is done by turning on or off the checkbox

switch allocated to each column, lying just below the column name.

Instead of clicking on the checkbox to change it, you can also click

on the column name.



Complementing of all columns is also possible via the corresponding

icon.



@{U}Setting the column order@{u}

The order of the columns can be changed in the same way as for a table

window. Just click on the column name with the left mouse button and

hold down the button while dragging it to the new position.



@{I}Note:@{i}

If an old query is loaded, then you will find left to right first

those columns that are to be output, as it is assumed that these will

be the columns of greatest interest.



@{U}Setting the column width@{u}

This is done in exactly the same way as for a table window, i.e. by

left-clicking on the solid dividing line at the top of the column and

dragging it to a new position while holding down the mouse key. During

this a small box shows the @{B}Width@{b} of the column and the @{B}Total@{b} width.

As for table windows the option is offered here to double-click on a

column name to open the @{"Column width dialog-box" LINK "Dialogbox Spaltenbreite"}.



@{U}Formulating the conditions@{u}

Formulation of the conditions is performed in the individual fields

of the matrix.

The following applies: All columns of a line are combined with a

logical AND. Individual lines in turn are combined with a logical OR.



The following mathematical relations can occur in a field:



@{I}Character             Meaning @{i}

@Line 1 56 0 0 1

=                     Equal

<> or !=              Not equal

>                     Larger than

>=                    Larger than or equal

<                     Smaller than

<=                    Smaller than or equal

[...] or BETWEEN      Between

{Any text}            interactive query parameter

{Maskname.Fieldname}  Field contents as query parameter



[...] here means for instance [b-d], which selects all terms from 'b'

up to 'd' inclusive. This has the same meaning as BETWEEN 'b' AND 'd'.



{Any text} represents a text that is displayed in a dialog-box, and

for whose field the value can then be set interactively.



{Maskname.Fieldname} represents the field name of an open mask. The

value input there will be used for the query.



After a relation you have to specify the comparison value. Comparison

will be made with the column in which the condition has been entered.



The following joker characters can be used for conditions in text

fields:



@{I}Character  Meaning @{i}

@Line 1 44 0 0 1

*          Any character-string (also empty)

?          Just one character of any kind

#          Any numeral



The joker '?' can also be used in Date fields to select individual

components. So ??.11.?? in a 'Birthday' field represents all persons

that have as birthday in November.



@{I}Note:@{i}

A single quote-mark (') may appear in a query condition only as a

separator of character-strings, not within a character-string.



If a query is to be formulated in which a single quote-mark appears

then a double-quote (") can be used as a separator.



@{U}Specifying the sorting order@{u}

The sorting order is specified via the Sorting order icon (@{B}+/-@{b}).

As an alternative it can be called also by a double right-click on

any field.



The command Execute starts a query. This process runs in the back-

ground. The sorting is performed exclusively.

Following this a @{"table window" LINK "Tabellen-Fenster"} is opened with the result. If the

@{B}Number of records for query@{b} switch in the @{"Configuration dialog-box" LINK "Dialogbox Konfiguration"}

is turned on then, before the window opens, an info-box shows the

number of data records found.



@endnode





@node "Abfrageliste-Fenster" "Query-list window"

@toc "The windows"

@{U}3.13  Query-list window [F6]                          PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This is a @{"table window" LINK "Tabellen-Fenster"} in which the names of the queries are shown.

If the window is enlarged, then the queries themselves can be looked

at as @{"SQL" LINK "Sidebar: SQL"} commands. The window has some additional features:



If a data record in this window is selected then the following actions

can be performed:

- Left double-click: Calling the Open command

- Right double-click: Calling the Execute command



When performing the @{B}Open@{b} command, unlike for normal table windows

this does not open a mask window, but a @{"query window" LINK "Abfrage-Fenster"} instead. This

window then contains the previously selected data record, making it

possible to modify previously saved queries. Should you nevertheless

want to define a query via a normal @{"mask window" LINK "Masken-Fenster"} (though this should

not be necessary as a rule), then after selection you can call the

Edit data command, which makes a mask appear.



@endnode





@node "Bericht-Fenster" "Report window"

