@node "table-clipboard window" "Table-clipboard window"

@toc "The windows"

@{U}3.17  Table-clipboard window                           PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This list window appears when you open a @{"table-clipboard icon" LINK "Tabellenklemmbrett-Sinnbild"}, either

by selecting it and then activating Open in the File menu, double-

clicking on it with the left mouse button, or by right-clicking on

the icon and then on @{B}@{Open ignore}@{b} in the popup.



The window contains data records that were extracted from a table

window by being dragged to the Manager's desktop, or if a query was

started that returned only a portion of an existing table; such a

partial set results when some of the search criteria used do not apply

to all of the data records.



The table-clipboard window is also known as a virtual window, because

its contents are not saved when you quit the program.



@endnode





@node "Report-Fenster" "Template window"

@toc "The windows"

@xref "SQL statement"

@xref "Summing"

@{U}3.18  Template window                                  PHOENIX Manager@{u}



A template is a kind of stencil which, besides normal text, can

contain placeholders for fields from the database. This stencil can

be combined (mixed) with default data records, so that each record

results in a discrete template.



A template window can be created by using the NewTemplate command in

the Process menu, as well as by the Open command as long as a data

record is selected in a @{"template-list window" LINK "Reportliste-Fenster"} during this.



The window's title line displays the name of the database.



The info line shows the current name of the template. Hence it will

be empty when dealing with a new template.



Below the info line are three popup listboxes. The first (@{B}Table@{b}) lets

you select the table, the second to choose a @{B}Field@{b} and the third

to select an @{B}Index@{b}.



The second and third popup listbox always offers the choice of the

fields and indices of the table selected in the first listbox.



Below this is an icon bar which can be used to enter a definition at

the current cursor position. The icons have the following meaning:



@image "TMPLICN.IMG" 0

## Oder fuer Farbaufloesungen

## @image "TMPLICNC.IMG" 0





                     1   2   3   4    5   6   7



   ˘ 1  Current date (SYSDATE)

   ˘ 2  Current time (SYSTIME)

   ˘ 3  Current date and time (SYSTIMESTAMP)

