@node "SQL statement"

@toc "Report-Fenster"

@{U}3.17.1  The SQL statement                              PHOENIX Manager@{u}



In addition to the branch operation '{>}' introduced earlier, PHOENIX

offers a further powerful tool for mixing data from several tables in

a template.



With the command '{$SQL=...}' an SQL statement can be executed, with

which you defined the data from the branching table more exactly.



When using the simple branching operation '{>}' it is only possible

to @{"branch" LINK "Branch"} to a table via an index. From this table all data records

that are present for this index will be output sequentially (i.e. in

the order they were input). This should certainly suffice for most

tasks. However, if a given type of sorting of data records in the

branching table is required, or if selection is to take place via

more complex criteria, you have to use the SQL command.



Sidebar: SQL



Like the branching operator, the SQL command can be inserted at any

desired place in the template:



{$SQL="SQL statement"}



SQL statement here is a character-string enclosed in double quotes,

which must be built up as follows (the SQL keywords are displayed

in bold):



"@{B}SELECT * FROM@{b} Table_name @{B}WHERE@{b} Field_name1=Value1 @{B}OR@{b} Field_name2=Value2

@{B}ORDER BY@{b} Field_name1 @{B}ASC@{b}, Field_name2 @{B}DESC@{b}"



The first part of the SQL command is always the same: SELECT * FROM.

This is followed by the name of the table from which the data are

to be fetched: Table_name. Following the keyword WHERE you formulate

the conditions that the data records of the destination table should

fulfill.

Condition linkages available are the two operators OR and AND.

Comparison operators available are <, =, > and <>. Optionally you

can also set a sorting order for the branch table. For this you can

enter after ORDER BY the sorting criteria, separated by commas. The

sorting criterium consists of a field name followed by ASC (ascending)

or DESC (descending). Specifying the sorting order is not mandatory

(default is ASC).



If you want to emulate simple branching via an SQL command then in

place of (Source_index>Destination_table.Destination_index) write:

{$SQL="SELECT * FROM Destination_table WHERE

Destination_index=Source_table.Source_index"}

You should note here that following WHERE you must always specify

the table name before the field name, unless this is a field in the

destination table.



If the data of the destination table are to be sorted according to a

given value, you would write:

{$SQL="SELECT * FROM Destination_table WHERE

Destination_index=Source_table.Source_index ORDER BY Field_name ASC"}



Following the SQL command you can use the fields of the destination

table in the template. In addition the fields of the parent tables

can be output directly. If names are duplicated, you can access a

field of the source table by specifying additionally the table name:

(Table_name.Field_name)



SQL branching is terminated by a branch return ({<}) command.



@endnode





@node "Summing"

@toc "Report-Fenster"

@{U}3.17.2  Summing                                        PHOENIX Manager@{u}



During the processing of a template there is a possibility to add up

all numeric fields. This sum can be output at the end of the template

or a branching process.



This is done with the '+' character.



@{I}Example:@{i}



     {Tape:3} {Remaining} min.

     {+}------------

      {Remaining:5} min.



All tapes with their remaining time are to be output in a list. After

this the total remaining time is to be output.

Result (for the first seven tapes):



     001  180 min.

     002   45 min.

     003    2 min.

     004   10 min.

     005    5 min.

     006   10 min.

     007    5 min.

     -------------

          257 min.



As you can see, the template definition will run through each tape.

However, not the whole definition will be used, but only that up to

the '+' character. The following part will be output only once at the

end (i.e. not for every tape).



It is also possible to sum numeric fields of data records while pro-

cessing a branch. The summing process then starts anew for each branch.



In the following example all tapes should be output with their titles

and playing time. The playing time of each title on one tape should be

added up, so that at the end of each tape its total playing time is

output.



The template definition has the following form:



Tape: {Tape}

------------

No. Title Playlength

-----------------------------

{Tape > VIDEO}

{COUNT:2}, {Title:-20} {Playlength}{+}

-----------------------------

Total: {Playlength:21}

{<}



@endnode





