@symbol ari "Database toolbox"



@{U}The database toolbox@{u}

At top left of the desktop is an area called the 'database toolbox'.

Here you can choose the database, the table and the index you want to

work with, and also whether the index is to be processed in ascending

or descending order. If no database has been loaded as yet, then all

fields will be empty. Only the sorting order for the next action

(@{B}Ascending@{b} or @{B}Descending@{b}) can be specified at this stage.



The topmost field shows the database currently being handled.

You can perform the following actions on this field:



Single left-click:

  Lets you select the current database in the listbox that drops down

Double left-click:

  Activates the Open (database) command

Double right-click:

  Activates the Database info command



The middle portion shows a list containing the tables present in the

current database; with long lists you can use the scroll arrows to

reveal further entries.

You can perform the following actions on the entries:



Single left-click:

  Selects the current table

Double left-click:

  Activates the Open table command

Double right-click:

  Activates the Table info command

Dragging to the @{"Wastebin icon" LINK "Papierkorb-Sinnbild"}:

  Activates the Delete command

Dragging to the @{"Printer icon" LINK "Drucker-Sinnbild"}:

  Activates the Print command

Dragging to the @{"Drive icon" LINK "Laufwerk-Sinnbild"}:

  Activates the Disk output command

Dragging to the @{"Clipboard icon" LINK "Klemmbrett-Sinnbild"}:

  Activates the @{"Export (to GEM clipboard)" LINK "To GEM clipboard"} command



The lower list shows the indices present in the current table; with

long lists you can use the scroll arrows to reveal further entries.

You can perform the following actions on the entries:



Single left-click:

  Selects the current index

Double left-click:

  Activates the Open table command

Double right-click:

  Activates the @{"index info" LINK "Index info"} command

Dragging to the @{"Wastebin icon" LINK "Papierkorb-Sinnbild"}:

  Activates the Delete command

Dragging to the @{"Printer icon" LINK "Drucker-Sinnbild"}:

  Activates the Print command

Dragging to the @{"Drive icon" LINK "Laufwerk-Sinnbild"}:

  Activates the Disk output command

Dragging to the @{"Clipboard icon" LINK "Klemmbrett-Sinnbild"}:

  Activates the @{"Export (to GEM clipboard)" LINK "To GEM clipboard"} command



At the lower edge of the toolbox are two radio buttons. With these

you can set the current direction in which tables will be output.

This can be either @{B}Ascending@{b} or @{B}Descending@{b}.

You can perform the following actions on the buttons or their legends:



Single click with either mouse button:

  Selects the current sorting direction

Double click with either mouse button:

  Activates the Open table command

Dragging to the @{"Wastebin icon" LINK "Papierkorb-Sinnbild"}:

  Activates the Delete command

Dragging to the @{"Printer icon" LINK "Drucker-Sinnbild"}:

  Activates the Print command

Dragging to the @{"Drive icon" LINK "Laufwerk-Sinnbild"}:

  Activates the Disk output command

Dragging to the @{"Clipboard icon" LINK "Klemmbrett-Sinnbild"}:

  Activates the @{"Export (to GEM clipboard)" LINK "To GEM clipboard"} command



If you want to change the display in the listboxes, click with the

right mouse button in a free space in the toolbox. A popup menu will

appear offering the following sorting criteria:



@{B}By name@{b}:

  Tables and indices will be displayed sorted by their names.

@{B}By number@{b}:

  Tables and indices will be displayed sorted by their number, i.e.

  in the order in which they were laid down in @{Designer ignore}.

Select the desired sorting method with a right-click on the relevant

popup entry.



In each case only the display of the current database is affected, so

that switching to another database the setting last valid there will

be retained.

The index 'Sequentiell' (= Sequential) is always displayed as the

first index entry, no matter whether you choose sorting @{B}By name@{b} or

@{B}By number@{b}.



@endnode





@node "Execute calculation"

@toc "Inhalt"

@{U}7  Execute calculation                                 PHOENIX Manager@{u}



The calculation will be performed as a background process. The data

record set to which the calculation is applied can be defined in

several ways:



  1. If no item is selected on the desktop or in a @{"table window" LINK "Tabellen-Fenster"},

     then the calculation will be performed for all data records of

     the current table of the @{"database toolbox" LINK "Schreibtisch des Managers" "Database toolbox"}.

  2. If a @{"table icon" LINK "Tabellen-Sinnbild"} or a @{"table-clipboard icon" LINK "Tabellenklemmbrett-Sinnbild"} is selected

     on the desktop, then the calculation will be performed for all

     data records of this icon.

  3. If some data records in a table window are selected, then the

     calculation will be performed with all selected data records.



To execute a calculation you can also drag a table from the database

toolbox, a table icon, or data records from a table window onto the

@{"calculation window" LINK "Rechnen-Fenster"}.



@endnode





@node "Execute template"

@toc "Inhalt"

@{U}8  Execute template                                    PHOENIX Manager@{u}



If a @{"template window" LINK "Report-Fenster"} is topped, then this template will be executed.

If a @{"table icon" LINK "Tabellen-Sinnbild"} or data records in a table are

selected, then Manager attempts to combine these data records with the

template, i.e. execute the template on these data records. If no

items are selected, then the table specified in the template will be

used as the data source.



A template can be executed only if does not contain any errors. If

errors occur, then they will be reported in an error-box, offering the

opportunity to correct them. The execution of a template runs as a

background process.



Before executing the template you must specify whether the template is

to be output to the @{B}Screen@{b}, a @{B}Printer@{b}, or to a @{B}File@{b}.



@{I}Note:@{i}

If the template is present in the 1st Word Plus format, then it has to

be output to a file, since the Manager can not print the Wordplus

format directly. However the template output file retains the Wordplus

attributes (bold, undeerscored etc.) as well as any incorporated

graphics. This file can be printed out later in the 1st Word Plus

program.



@endnode





