@node "Papierkorb-Sinnbild" "Wastebin icon"

@toc "Icons"

@{U}9.1  Wastebin icon                                     PHOENIX Manager@{u}



The wastebin is used for the deletion of data records. Tables or

individual data records can be dragged to it. There is only one

wastebin for all opened databases.



The wastebin always displays the deleted data records of the current

database. If you switch to another database, then the wastebin will

display the deleted data records of the new current database. The old

contents are not lost, however.



If all data records are to be restored again, then select the Wastebin

icon and then activate the Paste command in the Edit menu.



A double-click with the right mouse button activates the Info command.



If the @{"wastebin window" LINK "Papierkorb-Fenster"} is open, then alternatively data

records can be deleted as well, by dragging them onto the wastebin

window instead of the Wastebin icon.



@endnode





@node "Drucker-Sinnbild" "Printer icon"

@toc "Icons"

@xref "Dialogbox Drucker-Parameter" "Printer parameters dialog-box"

@{U}9.2  Printer icon                                      PHOENIX Manager@{u}



The printer serves for printing out tables. To output a table to the

printer, you have to drag it to the Printer icon. In addition, it is

possible to print individual data records of a table, by selecting

them in a window and the dragging them onto the Printer icon. The name

of the Printer icon displays either as 'PRINTER' or the name of the

currently loaded printer driver.



For more about printer drivers see the @{"Printer parameters dialog-box" LINK "Dialogbox Drucker-Parameter"}.



A double-click with the left mouse button on the Printer icon

activates the Printer parameters command.



A double-click with the right mouse button on the Printer icon

activates the Printer queue command.



@endnode





@node "Laufwerk-Sinnbild" "Drive icon"

@toc "Icons"

@{U}9.3  Drive icon                                        PHOENIX Manager@{u}



The Drive icon is used for outputting tables to a file. To do this,

the file has to be dragged to the Drive icon. In addition, it is

possible to output individual data records of a table to a file by

selecting them in a window and the dragging them onto the Drive icon.

A fileselector-box opens and waits for the input of a filename.



A double-click with the left mouse button on the Drive icon activates

the Open file command. This allows the contents of various files to

be displayed in windows. The following files are recognised:

- Files with GEM suffix (vector graphic)

- Files with IMG suffix (pixel graphic)

- Files with IND and DAT suffix (PHOENIX databases)

- Files with any other suffix (will be interpreted as text files)



In the last case the internal text editor will be called so that these

files can be modified as well and saved once more. A double-click with

the right mouse button activates the Info command.



@endnode





@node "Klemmbrett-Sinnbild" "Clipboard icon"

@toc "Icons"

@{U}9.4  Clipboard icon                                    PHOENIX Manager@{u}



The clipboard serves for exchanging data with other GEM programs via

the GEM clipboard. This icon appears @{I}only@{i} when the desk accessory

CLIPBRD.ACC is installed on the computer.



To transfer a table to the GEM clipboard you have to drag it onto the

Clipboard icon. In addition it is possible to transfer individual data

records of a table to a file in the GEM clipboard by selecting it in a

window and then dragging it onto the Clipboard icon. Then a file named

SCRAP.TXT will be created in the current GEM clipboard directory; this

is normally CLIPBRD in the root of drive C:. If such a file exists

already, it will be overwritten.



The format of this file corresponds to the format that would result if

the data records were exported to this file in ASCII format. Further

information about this can be found in the Export command chapter.



A double-click with the left mouse button opens the clipboard. This

then displays the contents of the GEM clipboard in a @{"clipboard window" LINK "Klemmbrett-Fenster"}.

The usage of this window is explained in the documentation for the

CLIPBRD desk accessory.



A double-click with the right mouse button activates the Info command.



@endnode





@node "Prozeû-Sinnbild" "Process icon"

@toc "Icons"

@{U}9.5  Process icon                                      PHOENIX Manager@{u}



The process icon appears when a @{"process window" LINK "Prozeû-Fenster"} is iconized. This is

achieved by using the @{B}@{Iconize ignore}@{b} button in the window, or executing the

Iconize command in the Edit menu when a process window is active. A

process icon always takes the name of the table taking part in the

process. An exception is the printer spooler, which always carries the

name SPOOLER.



A process window is created when an action is executed that takes some

time to compete. Such an action runs first in the background, so that

you can continue to work unhindered. These actions include:

- @{"Deletion" LINK "Delete"} of data records

- Restoration of data records

- Output of tables to a file

- @{"Printing" LINK "Print"} tables

- @{"Exporting" LINK "Export"} data records

- @{"Importing" LINK "Import"} data records

- Evaluation of queries

- Outputting reports and templates

- Automatic calculation of data



@{I}Note:@{i}

You should bear in mind that background processes require a large

amount of processing power. When such a process is running, then it

may happen - particularly with less powerful hardware and output to

floppy disk - that mouse operations become a little sluggish and the

computer no longer appears to react quickly enough. In particular, a

double-click of the mouse is then often skipped by the computer and

evaluated as two single-clicks. However, instead of a double-click

you can always use the Open command.



A maximum of six processes may run simultaneously.



A double-click on the icon with the left mouse button will open the

process window.



A double-click on the icon with the right mouse button will activate

the Info command.



A single click with the right mouse button makes a popup menu appear

with the three commands Info, Open a Remove. You can activate any of

these with a right-click.



 @{B}Info@{b}        shows current information about the process. It has the

             same effect as the Info command in the Help main menu.

 @{B}Open@{b}        opens the associated @{"process window" LINK "Prozeû-Fenster"}. It has the same

             effect as the Open command in the File main menu when a

             process icon is selected.

 @{B}Remove@{b}      terminates the process prematurely. It has the same

             effect as the Remove command in the Edit main menu.



After the completion or termination of a process its associated icon,

if present, vanishes automatically from the dektop without having to

activate a special command for this.



@endnode





@node "Tabellen-Sinnbild" "Table icon"

@toc "Icons"

@{U}9.6  Table icon                                        PHOENIX Manager@{u}



The table icon appears when a @{"table window" LINK "Tabellen-Fenster"} (list window) is iconized.

Such a window can be created with the Open table command. The result

of a query is also a table (or a @{"table-clipboard" LINK "table-clipboard window"}).



A maximum of 18 such icons (together with @{"table-clipboard icons" LINK "Tabellenklemmbrett-Sinnbild"}) can

be placed on the desktop.



A double-click on the icon with the left mouse button will open the

table window.



A double-click on the icon with the right mouse button will activate

the Info command.



@autorefoff

A single click with the @{I}right@{i} mouse button makes a popup menu appear

with the three commands @{B}Info@{b}, @{B}Open@{b} and @{B}Remove@{b}. You can activate any

of these with a @{I}right-click.@{i}

@autorefon



 @{B}Info@{b}        shows current information about the table window. It has

             the same effect as the Info command in the Help main

             menu.

 @{B}Open@{b}        opens the associated @{"table window" LINK "Tabellen-Fenster"}. It has the same

             effect as the Open command in the File main menu when a

             table icon is selected.

 @{B}Remove@{b}      Removes the icon from the dektop. It has the same

             effect as the Remove command in the Edit main menu.



@endnode





@node "Tabellenklemmbrett-Sinnbild" "Table-clipboard icon"

@toc "Icons"

@{U}9.7  Table-clipboard icon                              PHOENIX Manager@{u}



The table-clipboard icon appears when a @{"table window" LINK "Tabellen-Fenster"} (list window)

that displays an extract from a table is iconized. Such extracts can

be created as an icon by dragging data records from a table window

onto the desktop, or if a query is started which returns a portion

of an existing table; such a partial set results when some of the

search criteria do not apply to all of the data records.



The way this icon is used corresponds to that for the @{"table icon" LINK "Tabellen-Sinnbild"}. The

only exception is that you can not drag the icon onto the wastebin

icon or onto other table-clipboard icons.



Double-clicking the icon will open a table-clipboard window that

displays the data records that were extracted from the original table.

Alternatively you can select the icon and then activate Open in the

File menu, or right-click on it and then on @{B}@{Open ignore}@{b} in the popup.



A maximum of 18 such icons (together with table icons) can be placed

on the desktop.



@endnode





@node "Sidebar: SQL"

