@node "ABS"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.1  ABS                                               PHOENIX Manager@{u}



Calculates the absolute value of a number. The absolute value of a

number is its amount and is always positive.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}

Result=ABS(Value);



@{B}Value@{b} is any number (a constant, Floating-point or Number field, a

variable).



Note that you @{I}must@{i} use a comma as the decimal separator, not a point!



@{I}Examples:@{i}

ABS(4,6) results in 4,6.

ABS(-24) results in 24.

ABS(0) results in 0.



@endnode





@node "ACOS"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.2  ACOS                                              PHOENIX Manager@{u}



Calculates the arc cosine of a number. It is the inverse function

of COS.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}

Result = ACOS(Value);



@{B}Value@{b} is any number (a constant, Floating-point or Number field, a

variable). ACOS expects a value in the range -1..+1 and returns

the associated angle in radians.



Note that you @{I}must@{i} use a comma as the decimal separator, not a point!



@{I}Example:@{i}

ACOS(-0,678) results in 2,315835.



@endnode





@node "Alert"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.3  Alert                                             PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This function outputs an alert box with information for the user to

the screen. The alert box can contain up to four lines of text, which

can be combined with one of four icons.

In addition an alert box can display up to five buttons. The return

will be the number of the button clicked on, where the buttons are

numbered from the left starting with 1.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}

Result=ALERT("[Icon][Text][Buttons][Pattern][Help]");



To explain the individual parameters:



@{B}Icon@{b} determines the pictogram that is to appear of the left side of

the box:

0 = @{Info ignore} icon

1 = Exclamation mark

2 = Question mark

3 = Stop sign

4 = No icon



The number must be enclosed in square brackets.



@{B}Text@{b} can be any desired text-string. Up to 4 lines @ 40 characters can

be displayed. The individual lines must be separated by a vertical

line ('|') from each other. The text must be enclosed in square

brackets.



@{B}Buttons@{b} are used to define the buttons with which the box can be quit.

A maximum of 5 buttons are possible. The button legends must again be

separated by vertical bars ('|') from each other. If the button is to

be selectable from the keyboard ([Alternate]+[Letter]) then a tilde

('~') must be inserted in front of the relevant letter.



@{B}Pattern@{b} assigns a special meaning to the buttons and can be used

optionally to produce a bell sound on opening the box.

The following order applies for this:

[Bell|No.OK-button|No.Cancel-button|No.Help-button ].



For @{B}Bell@{b} if '1' is specified then the bell will sound, with '0' it

will not.

In the other three fields you should specify which buttons are to

contain the meaning of the @{B}OK@{b}, @{B}Cancel@{b} or @{B}Help@{b} button; for this the

buttons are numbered from the left starting with 1.

If no default meaning is to be assigned, you have to specify '-1'.



@{B}Help@{b} contains a cross-reference to the entry in the Help database for

which information is to be displayed when activating the button

defined as the Help-button. (Note that this is not Help for Manager

itself, but one created for the specific database.)



If you do not specify a character here, branching to the Help database

will not take place. Since you can modify Help databases yourself (see

Appendix A in the PHOENIX manual), you can display information for the

current calculation or database with this entry.





@{I}Examples:@{i}

a)

  VAR b;

  b=ALERT("[3][Line1|Line2][Button ~1|Button ~2][0|1|1|-1][]");

b)

  VAR b;

  b=ALERT("[1][Default buttons][OK|Cancel|Help][1|1|2|3][Index]");



A click on 'Help' displays the index of the online help.



@endnode





@node "ASIN"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.4  ASIN                                              PHOENIX Manager@{u}



Calculates the arc sine of a number. It is the inverse function of

SIN.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}

Result=ASIN(Value);



@{B}Value@{b} is any number (a constant, Floating-point or Number field, a

variable). ASIN expects a value in the range -1..+1 and returns

the associated angle in radians.



Note that you @{I}must@{i} use a comma as the decimal separator, not a point!



@{I}Example:@{i}

ASIN(0,543) results in 0,574006.



@endnode





@node "Assignment operator"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.5  Assignment operator: =                            PHOENIX Manager@{u}



The assignment operator is the basic operation for the calculation

function. It is used to assign to the variable or field on its left-

hand side the value of the right-hand side.



For instance, the entry

@autorefoff

SUM=FIELD1+FIELD2;

has the effect that the field SUM is assigned the result of the

@autorefon

addition of the fields FIELD1 and FIELD2. During this an attempt will

be made always to convert the result to the data type of the field on

the left. So, say, if a Text field is assigned a number, then this

number will be converted to a character-string at first. If the

left-hand side of the assignment contains a variable, then it will

take the data type of the right-hand side automatically.



@endnode





@node "ATAN"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.6  ATAN                                              PHOENIX Manager@{u}



Calculates the arc tangent of a number. It is the inverse function of

TAN.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}

Result=ATAN(Value);



@{B}Value@{b} is any number (a constant, Floating-point or Number field, a

variable). ATAN expects any value and returns the associated angle

in radians.



Note that you @{I}must@{i} use a comma as the decimal separator, not a point!



@{I}Example:@{i}

ATAN(456,78) results in 0,574006.



@endnode





@node "AVG"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.7  AVG                                               PHOENIX Manager@{u}



Ascertains the average of any desired field for all data records of

the destination table that were stored with a given index.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}

Result=AVG("Fieldname;Source_index>DEST_TABLE.Dest_index");



@{B}Fieldname@{b} is the field of the DEST_TABLE for which the average is

to be obtained.



@{I}Example:@{i}

see MAX.



@endnode





@node "Basic arithmetic types"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.8  Basic arithmetic types: +, -, *, /                PHOENIX Manager@{u}



The basic arithmetic types will be well known. + represents addition,

- subtraction, * multiplication and / division. These operators may

be applied to fields of the data type Number, Long and Floating-point

without restriction.



For Text fields and fields of the @{"External file" LINK "DESIGNER.HYP/Data types" 40} type, you can only

use the operator +. The addition of two character-strings corresponds

to the concatenation of the character-strings.



For Date, Time and Timestamp fields you can only apply the addition

and subtraction operators. The subtraction of two Date fields returns

the number of days between the two dates; the result can be assigned

to a field of the data type Number, Long or Floating-point.



To a Time field you can only sensibly add another Time field. The

subtraction of two time values returns a duration (time interval) in

the format HHMMSSmmmmmm (the small 'm' represents microseconds).



To a field of the type TIMESTAMP you can add Date and Time fields.

The subtraction of two TIMESTAMP values returns a time interval in

the format: DDMMYYYYHHMMSSmmmmmm (Day, Month, Year, Hours, Minutes,

Seconds, microseconds).



@endnode





@node "CHAR"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.9  CHAR                                              PHOENIX Manager@{u}



Converts a value to a character-string.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}

Result=CHAR(Value);



@{B}Value@{b} is any number (a constant, Floating-point or Number field, a

variable).



@{I}Examples:@{i}

CHAR(123,45) creates the character-string '123,45'.

CHAR(51) creates the character-string '51'.



@endnode





@node "CHR"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.10  CHR                                              PHOENIX Manager@{u}



Converts a number between 0 and 255 to the associated ASCII value.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}

Result=CHR(Value);



@{B}Value@{b} is a number between 0 and 255.



@{I}Example:@{i}

CHR(65) creates the character 'A'.

CHR(13)+CHR(10) creates the (otherwise not directly inputtable)

character-string 'CR/LF' ('Carriage return/Line feed'), i.e. a line

feed.



@endnode





@node "Comparison operators"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.11  Comparison operators: <, <=, ==, >, =>, <>       PHOENIX Manager@{u}



<  means smaller than

<= means smaller than or equal

== means equal

>  means larger than

=> means larger than or equal

<> means smaller or larger than (i.e. @{I}not@{i} equal)



These operators compare their operands with each other. The returned

result shows whether the specified condition applies (TRUE, value 1)

or not (FALSE, value 0).



@{I}Example:@{i}

Let FIELD1 and FIELD2 be of the type Number. FIELD1 contains the

value 4 and FIELD2 contain the value 9. The expression FIELD1<FIELD2

therefore returns just like the expression FIELD1<=FIELD2 the value

TRUE, while FIELD1>FIELD2 naturally returns the value FALSE.



Here it is imperative to note that for a test of equality you have

to use the operator ==, since a single equality sign is already in

use as the assignment operator!



@endnode





@node "COS"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.12  COS                                              PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This calculates the cosine of a number.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}

Result=COS(Value);



@{B}Value@{b} is any number (a constant, Floating-point or Number field, a

variable). COS expects a value in radians (0¯=0*pi rad, 90¯=pi/2 rad,

180¯=pi rad, 270¯=3pi/2 rad, 360¯=2pi rad etc.) as argument and

returns the associated cosine.



Note that you @{I}must@{i} use a comma as the decimal separator, not a point!



@{I}Example:@{i}

COS(3,141) results in -1,0.



@endnode





@node "COUNT"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.13  COUNT                                            PHOENIX Manager@{u}



COUNT returns the number of the current data record and will be

incremented automatically during the calculation process record by

record.



@{U}Syntax and example:@{u}

Number=COUNT;



With this the data records of a table can be numbered in sequence

automatically. At the end, the field @{B}Number@{b} will contain the data

record number of each record.



@endnode





@node "DATE"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.14  DATE                                             PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This converts a character-string to a Date field.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}

Datefield=DATE(Characterstring);



@endnode





@node "DAY"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.15  DAY                                              PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This ascertains the Day from a given Date field.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}

Day=DAY(Datefield)



@endnode





@node "ERRNO"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.16  ERRNO                                            PHOENIX Manager@{u}



Returns the status of the calculation operation.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}

Result=ERRNO();



If an error occurred at the last calculation operation, then this

function returns a positive error-code, else the number 0.



Here the following mean:

Error-code 33: Argument outside permissible calculation range.

Error-code 34: Result outside permissible calculation range.



In addition each calculation function returns as a result 0,0.



@{I}Example:@{i}

VAR b,x;

x=SQRT(-1);

IF ERRNO<>0 THEN

    b=ALERT("[3][Error!][~Cancel][0|1|1|-1][]");

END;



@endnode





@node "EXIT"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.17  EXIT                                             PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This permits the premature termination of a calculation.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}

EXIT;



@{I}Example:@{i}

...

button=ALERT(...);

IF button==! THEN

    EXIT;

END;

...



@endnode





@node "EXP"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.18  EXP                                              PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This is the exponential function, calculating e^x, where e is the

base of the natural logarithm (2.718281...).



@{U}Syntax:@{u}

Result=EXP(Value);



@{B}Value@{b} is any number (a constant, Floating-point or Number field, a

variable).



Note that you @{I}must@{i} use a comma as the decimal separator, not a point!



@{I}Example:@{i}

EXP(2,0) results in 7,389056.



@endnode





@node "EXPORT"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.19  EXPORT                                           PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This saves the contents of any field (Text, Number, Graphic, @{"BLOB" LINK "DESIGNER.HYP/Data types" 72}...)

to a file.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}

Result=EXPORT(Filename,Fieldname);



 @{B}Filename@{b}   should contain the complete access path, including the

            drive/partition name.

 @{B}Fieldname@{b}  can be any field.



@{U}Result@{u}



  0  OK

  1  File does not exist

  4  File can not be written

  5  File can not be created

  7  Insufficient free memory available



@{I}Example:@{i}

VAR Filename, Result;

Filename="C:\CLIPBRD\SCRAP.TXT";

Result=EXPORT(Filename, Telephone);



saves the contents of the field @{B}Telephone@{b} to the GEM clipboard.



@endnode





@node "FIELD"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.20  FIELD                                            PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This function can be used within a calculation function to 'assemble'

the name of a field from a character-string, whose contents can then

be modified further or to which a new value can be assigned.



This function can be useful when the fields of a table should have

given values preassigned to them and the names of these fields differ

from each other only by a number in the last position. If, say, your

table contains the fields FIELD1 to FIELD6 and you want to assign the

number 0 to all fields in which no value has been entered yet, then

write the following calculation:



VAR i;

i = 0;

WHILE i <= 6 DO

    IF FIELD(  "FIELD" + i ) == NULL THEN

        FIELD( "FIELD" + i ) = 0;

    END;

    i = i + 1;

END;



@endnode





@node "FIRST"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.21  FIRST                                            PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This ascertains the lowest value of an index field.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}



Result=FIRST(Indexfield);



@endnode





@node "FLOAT"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.22  FLOAT                                            PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This converts any value to a floating-point number.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}

Result=FLOAT(Value);



@{B}Value@{b} is a character-string or number.



@{I}Example:@{i}

FLOAT("012,34") results in 12,34.



@endnode





@node "Formatting operator"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.23  Formatting operator                              PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This fills a character-string with space characters.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}



Result = string : number;



The character-string @{B}string@{b} will be filled with space characters up

to @{B}number@{b} characters, ranged right. The result will be assigned to

the field or variable @{B}Result@{b}.



Result = string : -number;



The character-string @{B}string@{b} will be filled with space characters up

to @{B}number@{b} characters, ranged left. The result will be assigned to

the field or variable @{B}Result@{b} or can be used further immediately.



@{I}Example:@{i}

NameWithDots=REPLACE(Forename:20," ",".");



fills with dots instead of blanks.



@endnode





@node "GET"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.24  GET                                              PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This fetches a value from a different table.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}

Result=GET("Field_to_read;Source_index>Dest_table.Dest_index");



@{B}Field_to_read@{b} is the name of the field in the destination table whose

value is to be fetched.

@{B}Source_index@{b} is the name of the index field in the source table, over

which the branching should take place.

@{B}Dest_table@{b} is the name of the table to which @{B}Field_to_read@{b} belongs.

@{B}Dest_index@{b} is an index field of the destination table and designates

the data record from which reaading should take place.

Only that data record in which the source index and destination index

have the same value will be read.



@{I}Example:@{i}

See PUT function.



@endnode





@node "HOUR"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.25  HOUR                                             PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This ascertains the hour from a specified Time field.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}

Result=HOUR(timefield);



@{I}Example:@{i}

HOUR(08:36:00) results in 8.



@endnode





@node "IF-THEN-ELSE-END"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@xref "Logical operators"

@{U}A.26  IF-THEN-ELSE-END                                 PHOENIX Manager@{u}



IF-THEN-ELSE-END is also called 'conditional branching' and makes it

possible to perform certain operations dependent on logical values.

Thus which part of the calculation is to be performed can depend on

a condition, for instance.



The condition should be formulated following the keyword IF. If the

condition applies, i.e. the logical expression has the value TRUE,

then the directives following the keyword THEN will be performed.

In addition further directives can follow the keyword ELSE; these

directives will be performed only if the condition following IF do

not apply, so the THEN branch is not traversed. However, the ELSE

branch can also be omitted if it is not required.



The end of an IF-THEN-ELSE structure is always flagged with the key-

word END.



Several IF-THEN-ELSE-END structures may be nested one after the other.



@{I}Example:@{i}

IF (InvoiceDate>PeriodEnd) | (InvoiceNo <=0) THEN

    IF (InvoiceAmount>500)&(ReminderProcess==0) THEN

        ReminderProcess=1;

    END;

    Reminder=1;

ELSE

    Reminder=0;

END;



@{I}See also:@{i}

Logical operators



@endnode





@node "IMPORT"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.27  IMPORT                                           PHOENIX Manager@{u}



Assigns to (any desired) field the contents of a file.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}

Result=IMPORT(Filename,Fieldname);



 @{B}Filename@{b}   is a Text field or a variable containing the complete

            access path, including the drive/partition name.

 @{B}Fieldname@{b}  is the name of any desired Number, Text, Graphic or

            @{"BLOB" LINK "DESIGNER.HYP/Data types" 72} field.



@{U}Result@{u}



  0  OK

  1  File does not exist

  2  File can not be opened

  3  File can not be read

  6  File has wrong format

  7  Insufficient free memory available



@{I}Example:@{i}

VAR Filename, Result;

Filename="C:\PAPILLON\IMAGES\ERDBEERE.IMG";

Result=EXPORT(Filename, IMAGE);



imports the file @{B}ERDBEERE.IMG@{b} into the graphic field @{B}Image@{b}.



@endnode





@node "KEYCOUNT"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.28  KEYCOUNT                                         PHOENIX Manager@{u}



Ascertain how frequently the index field of (another) table contains

a given value.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}

Number=KEYCOUNT("DestIndex;SourceIndex>DestTable.DestIndex");



As Result one obtains how often the key @{B}DestIndex@{b} in the destination

table has the value @{B}Value@{b}.



@{I}Example:@{i}

VAR Invoices;

Invoices=KEYCOUNT("ClientNo;ClientNo>INVOICES.ClientNo");



ascertains how many @{B}Invoices@{b} for the client @{B}ClientNo@{b} are present in

the table @{B}INVOICES@{b}.



@endnode





@node "LAST"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.29  LAST                                             PHOENIX Manager@{u}



Ascertains the highest value of an index field.



