@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.42  POW                                              PHOENIX Manager@{u}



Power function.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}

Result=POW(x,y);



This calculates the yth power of x (i.e. x^y).

@{B}x@{b} and @{B}y@{b} are floating-point values.



@{I}Example:@{i}

POW(2,3) results in 8.



@endnode





@node "PUT"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.43  PUT                                              PHOENIX Manager@{u}



Enters a value into the field of another table.



@{U}Syntax:@{u}



Result=PUT("Field_to_alter;SourceIndex>DestTable.DestIndex",Value);



@{B}Field_to_alter@{b} is the name of the field in the destination table into

which the value @{B}Value@{b} is to be entered. @{B}SourceIndex@{b} is the name of the

index field in the source table via which the branching is to take

place. @{B}DestTable@{b} is the name of the table to which the @{B}Field_to_alter@{b}

belongs. @{B}DestIndex@{b} is an index field of the destination table and it

determines the data record that is to be altered. The data record

that will be altered is the one in which @{B}SourceIndex@{b} and @{B}DestIndex@{b}

have the same value.



An example follows of an extract from a small bookkeeping calculation

with stock management. The table @{B}BALANCES@{b} contains the individual

invoice balances. Here the index key @{B}ProductNo@{b} is used to branch to

the @{B}PRODUCTSTOCK@{b} and there the @{B}Number@{b} of articles sold is subtracted

from the @{B}StockPosition@{b}.



VAR No_of_articles, Button, Result;

No_of_articles=GET(

"StockPosition;ProductNo>PRODUCTSTOCK.ProductNo");

IF No_of_articles<Number THEN

    Button=ALERT(

          "[3][Article not in stock!][~Cancel][0|1|1|-1][]");

ELSE

    Result=PUT(

    "StockPosition;ProductNo>PRODUCTSTOCK.ProductNo",No-of-articles-Number);

    IF Result!=0 THEN

        Button=ALERT("[3][Error with PUT command!][~Cancel][0|1|1|-1][]");

    END;

END;



@endnode





