@node "VAR"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.65  VAR                                              PHOENIX Manager@{u}



Within a calculation it is possible to define up to 32 variables. The

variables will be treated like fields. You can assign to them values

of other fields or variables, or assign their value to other fields.

The variables have no set data type; they assume automatically the

type of the expression that is assigned to them.



The assignment 'a=3' assigns to the variable @{B}a@{b} the number @{B}3@{b}. The

variable can now be reused like a field of the type Number.



Variables have to be defined at the start of the calculation. The

keyword VAR denotes the start of a variable definition. In one line

following VAR you can declare several variables, separated by commas.

If the variable definition extends over several lines, then you have

to write VAR at the start of each line. The variable name is not case

sensitive. The first 15 characters of the variable name are used to

differentiate the variables from each other.



@endnode





@node "WHILE-DO-END"

@toc "Calculation commands"

@{U}A.66  WHILE-DO-END                                     PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This serves for programming a loop. The assignments that follow the

keyword DO are repeated until the logical expression following WHILE

no longer has the value TRUE, but returns the value FALSE. (The

difference from REPEAT-UNTIL is that there the condition is only

checked at the end of the loop and hence the loop is always traversed

at least once; here the WHILE condition is checked immediately and

the function will be terminated as soon as it is FALSE.)



@{I}Example:@{i}



VAR counter, a;

counter=1; a=10;

WHILE counter<=10 DO

  a=a*10; counter=counter+1;

END;



The loop will be traversed ten times.



@endnode





