@node "Dialogbox Im/Export-Parameter" "Im/Export parameters dialog-box"

@toc "The dialog-boxes"

@autorefoff

@{U}B.13  Im/Export parameters dialog-box                  PHOENIX Manager@{u}

@autorefon



 ˘ The @{B}Separator characters@{b} area allows you to set the characters to

   be used for delimiting data records and fields when the data

   records are output in ASCII format.



 @{B}Record@{b} sets the separation characters that are written after each

     data record during @{"export" LINK "Export"}. These are specified in decimals from

     the ASCII table; 13 corresponds to a carriage return (CR), 10 to

     a linefeed (LF). The individual characters are separated by a

     comma. You can also specify character-strings if these are

     enclosed in quote-marks; it does not matter whether these are

     single ('xxxx') or double ("xxxx") quotes.



 @{B}Field@{b} sets the separation characters that are written after each

     field during export. These are specified in decimals from the

     ASCII table; 13 corresponds to a carriage return (CR), 10 to a

     linefeed (LF). The individual characters are separated by a

     comma. You can also specify character-strings if these are

     enclosed in quote-marks; it does not matter whether these are

     single ('xxxx' or double ("xxxx") quotes.



 @{B}Text@{b} specifies whether and through which characters Text fields can

     be enclosed. Some databases require such characters.

     So if for instance each Text field should be enclosed in double

     quotes, then you should enter the value '"' or 34 in this field.





 ˘ In the @{B}Conversion area:



 @{B}Export@{b} offers an option to set a given character coding, specially

     for accented/umlaut characters that often have different coding

     on various computer systems. But to use this, you have to install

     KEYTAB by Martin ElsÑsser on your Atari!





 ˘ In the @{B}Format@{b} area you have various formats available that are to

   be paid regard to during @{"importing" LINK "Import"} and @{"exporting" LINK "Export"}.



 With @{B}Binary@{b} selected, the data records can be exported in binary

     format. This is the shortest and quickest format, and is particu-

     larly useful if graphics or sound fields exist in a table.



 With @{B}ASCII@{b} selected, the data records can be exported in ASCII

     format. This is a pure text format and is particularly suitable

     for data exchange with other programs.



 With @{B}Column names@{b} switched on, an additional header is written

     before the first data record that specifies the field names.

     This will be required if data are to be processed further with

     the circular letter function of a text processor (e.g. Signum!4).



 @{B}Decimal point@{b} sets the format of the decimal divider. It is used

     when @{"exporting" LINK "Export"} decimal numbers and may not be left empty.





 ˘ In the @{B}Dates@{b} area you can choose in which format Date fields are

   imported and exported:



 If @{B}DD.MM.YYYY@{b}, @{B}MM.DD.YY@{b} or @{B}YYYY.MM.DD@{b} is selected, then the Date

     fields can be exported or imported in the corresponding format.



 If @{B}Days since 01.01.1900@{b} is selected, then the Date fields will be

     exported or imported as numbers, which specify the number of days

     since 01.01.1900. Some spreadsheets programs require this format.





 ˘ In the @{B}@{Import ignore} mode@{b} area you can decide how data records are to be

   imported:



 If @{B}Insert@{b} is selected then during @{"import" LINK "Import"} each read data record will

     be inserted anew.



 If @{B}Replace@{b} is selected then during import each read data record will

     be either inserted or modified. It will be inserted if it is not

     yet present in the database, else modified if it is already in

     the database. The Manager recognises this from the primary key

     of the read-in data record matching that of a data record that's

     already present in the table.



 @{B}Load...@{b} serves for loading the import/export parameters from a text

     file previously saved with:



 @{B}@{Save ignore}...@{b} which saves the parameters displayed in this dialog-box to

     a text file.



@endnode





