@{U}B.17  Open database dialog-box                         PHOENIX Manager@{u}

@autorefon



## @limage H:\SRC\PHOENIX\SRC\MANAGER\DOKU\UDO\picture\IMG\DATOEFFN.img 0

@LImage "OPENDB.IMG" 0

 @{B}Database@{b} displays the database that was selected earlier with the

     fileselector-box.



 @{B}User@{b} must be filled out if this database was protected by the data-

     base administrator. This can be done in the @{Designer ignore} program.

     The database administrator must then have assigned a user name

     to you under which you can modify the database.



 @{B}Password@{b} must be filled out when you were entered as a user by the

     database administrator and then created a password for yourself

     at sime time. The creation or changing of the password is done

     with the command Change password.





 ˘ In the @{B}Cache area@{b} you can make settings affecting the caches:



 @{B}Index cache@{b} allows you to enter the amount of memory (in KB) that

     is to be reserved for the index file.



 @{B}Data cache@{b} allows you to enter the amount of memory (in KB) that

     is to be reserved for the data file.



 @{B}Write index@{b} checkbox must be switched on if the index file is to be

     updated immediately at each write process, i.e. saved to a floppy

     or hard disk. If this is switched off then the index file will

     be updated only on closing the database. Alternatively to this

     the command @{B}Write cache@{b} in the Options menu will update the

     index file 'by hand'.



 @{B}Write data@{b} checkbox must be switched on if the data file is to be

     updated immediately at each write process, i.e. saved to a floppy

     or hard disk. If this is switched off then the data file will

     be updated only on closing the database. Alternatively to this

     the command @{B}Write cache@{b} will update the data file 'by hand'.

     If this switch is turned off and the computer crashes, then any

     changes made since the last Save will be lost.



     @{I}Note:@{i}

     In multi-user or multi-tasking operation the index and data files

     are always updated continuously, so that these two switches have

     no effect.





 ˘ In the @{B}Mode@{b} area, selection buttons determine in which operational

     mode the database is to be opened. Selecting the radio button:



 @{B}Single user (exclusive)@{b} means that you can use the database only if

     you are the only user at the time. This is the mode in which you

     will normally use the database.



 @{B}Multi-tasking@{b} means that you can call up the database on a computer

     running a multitasking operating system together with several

     other applications running simultaneously. This slows down the

     speed of operation.



 @{B}Multi-user@{b} means that you can use the database together with other

     users in a networked environment.

     A prerequisite for this is that no other user has logged into the

     database exclusively. In addition the operating system must be

     capable of being able to handle files from several processes at

     the same time as well as being able to lock a file. If the latter

     is not the case, a corresponding warning message will be output

     on opening the database.



 The @{B}Read-only@{b} checkbox must be switched on if the database should

     only be read, not written to. This may be necessary if the data-

     base lies on a write-protected medium, a CD-ROM, or has a table

     of contents which may not be written to by a given user.

     Once it is opened, such a database can not be modified.



