     The icons can be clicked on and produce variables that are then

     inserted at the current cursor position in the @{B}Header@{b} or @{B}Footer@{b}

     editable fields. The variables and their meanings are listed

     below and correspond to the icons left to right:



          @{I}Variable  Meaning @{i}

@Line 11 47 0 0 1

          $B        Database name

          $S        Sorting (table and the current index)

          $P        Page number

          $D        Date (the current date)

          $T        Time (the current time)





 ˘ The @{B}Paper@{b} area contains information about the current width

   and length of a page.



 @{B}Width@{b} sets the width of a page in characters.



 @{B}Length@{b} sets the length of a page in lines.



 @{B}Top marg@{b} sets the number of lines to be left free at the top of the

     page.



 @{B}Bottom marg@{b} sets the number of lines to be left free at the bottom

     of the page.



 @{B}Header marg@{b} sets the number of lines in the header area. If this

     field is set to 0 then no header will be output even if a header

     has been defined.



 @{B}Footer marg@{b} sets the number of lines in the footer area. If this

     field is set to 0 then no footer will be output even if a footer

     has been defined.



 @{B}Lines/page@{b} shows the resulting number of lines actually available

     with the above settings, i.e. the length of the page less all

     margins and any column header that may be present. It is equal

     to the number of data records that will fit on one page.



 @{B}Left marg@{b} sets the number of characters to be left free as the left

     edge of the page.





 ˘ The @{B}Switches@{b} area offers some options that are paid regard to when

   outputting to a table. However they apply only to outputs to disk

   or printer.



 If @{B}Formfeed@{b} is switched on, then a formfeed will be created after

     the output of each table to the printer.



 If @{B}Column headers@{b} is switched on, then on outputting a table to disk

     or printer each new page will be prefaced by a header containing

     the column names; this is followed by a line with separation

     dashes.



 If @{B}Summing@{b} is switched on, then a total sum of all numeric fields in

     the list will be output at the end of the table. If additionally

     a value is entered into the @{B}Group@{b} field, then intermediate sums

     will be output as well.



 @{B}Group@{b} sets the number of places paid regard to for group division.

     You can also regard this number as a sort of 'sensitivity'. The

     larger it is the more places will be paid regard to in the group

     division. This group division relates to the current index key

     by which the table is sorted for output. All data records whose

     first 'x' positions match belong to the same group. Here 'x' is

     the number that was entered in the @{B}Group@{b} field. Each group is

     separated from the next one by an empty line.



     @{I}Note:@{i}

     If @{U}Summing@{u} is switched on as well, then a subtotal of all numeric

     values wil be output after each group. At the end of the complete

     list a total will be output as well.



 @{B}Load...@{b} serves for loading page formats from a previously saved

     text file. The parameters loaded will then be displayed in the

     dialog-box.



 @{B}@{Save ignore}...@{b} serves for saving the parameters displayed in this dialog-box

     to a text file, where they are available for reuse.



@endnode





@node "Dialogbox Drucker-Parameter" "Printer parameters dialog-box"

@toc "The dialog-boxes"

@autorefoff

@{U}B.19  Printer parameters dialog-box                    PHOENIX Manager@{u}

@autorefon



The printer icon shows the currently loaded printer driver. Clicking

on this icon allows you to load a new driver (with a .PRT extension).



Please take note that the settings made here apply only for direct

printouts, not for the graphical printouts of the report via NVDI.



 @{B}Control chars@{b} allows you to input additional control characters to be

     sent to the printer before printing starts. These may be control

     characters to place the printer in a defined state. The control

     characters should be explained in the manual for the relevant

     printer. The format corresponds to the @{B}Record@{b} field in the

     @{"Im/Export parameters dialog-box" LINK "Dialogbox Im/Export-Parameter"}.



 @{B}Output files@{b} must have the editable field completed if output is to

     be 'printed' to a file rather than a printer. You can type in the

     full path directly, but it is more convenient to double-click on

     the legend in front of the editable field to open a fileselector

     where you can set the desired path and filename. For this to work

     the @{B}File@{b} radio button has to be switched on in the @{B}Output device@{b}

     area.





 ˘ The @{B}@{Font ignore}@{b} area lets you select various fonts and attributes that

     are available for printout:



     @{B}Pica@{b} or @{B}Elite@{b} specify the matching font. With Pica you generally

     have 10 characters per inch printed, so that on a DIN A4 page 80

     characters will fit in a line across the paper (without margins).

     With Elite this is 12 characters per inch, so that 96 characters

     will fit in a line.

     @{B}Narrow@{b}, @{B}Small@{b}, @{B}Wide@{b}, @{B}Italic@{b}, @{B}Bold@{b} and @{B}NLQ@{b} checkboxes modify the

     font set by the radio buttons. Their availability depends on the

     printer driver being used.





 ˘ @{B}Output device@{b} specifies the port to be used for output:



 If @{B}Spooler@{b} is switched on then the incorporated spooler will be used.

     During printing output will be to a temporary file at first and

     then passed on by the Spooler to the printer in the background.

     This can be an advantage since output to a file is faster than

     to a fairly slow printer. However, this requires external storage

     space in which the temporary file is created; after printing this

     will be deleted again. The Spooler is not active if the @{B}File @{b}

     radio button is switched on as well.



 If @{B}File@{b} is selected, then output will not be to a printer but to a

     file, which can be specified in the @{B}Output files@{b} editable field.



 With the @{B}PRN@{b} radio button selected, output will be to the printer

     that is connected to the parallel port of the computer.

     If @{B}Spooler@{b} is activated as well, output will be first to a

     temporary file, then in the backround to the printer.



 With the @{B}AUX@{b} radio button selected, output will be to the printer

     that is connected to the serial port of the computer.

     If @{B}Spooler@{b} is activated as well, output will be first to a

     temporary file, then in the backround to the printer.





 ˘ In the @{B}Line spacing@{b} area you can set the spacing with which the

     lines of a table or a template are output:



 With @{B}1/6@{b} selected the separation will be 1/6 inch. With this up to

     70 lines will fit on a DIN A4 page (without margins; in practice

     this will be a maximum of 66 printable lines).

## Die Anzahl im Original war falsch - 72 Zeilen passen nur auf 12 Zoll

## Endlospapier! Mit einzelnen Blaettern muss der Drucker sie auch halten!

## Auch stand dort 'mit Seitenrand' was nicht stimmt!



 With @{B}1/8@{b} selected the separation will be 1/8 inch. With this up to

     92 lines will fit on a DIN A4 page (without margins; in practice

     this will be a maximum of 88 printable lines).

## Wie oben





 ˘ In the @{B}Spooler parameters@{b} area you can decide how fast the Spooler

     is to operate. As a printer is a slow device, there may be times

     when the computer outputs a character but the printer can not

     handle the character quickly enough. As a result the program is

     halted and has to wait for the printer. On the other hand, if the

     program does not output the characters fast enough to the printer

     then this is not working at full capacity. The consequence: The

     printer prints a line now and again and rests inbetween.



 The @{B}Events/sec@{b} editable field lets you set the number of events that

     the next Spooler process to start is to receive. Sensible values

     lie between 1 and 100. It specifies the number of passes that a

     process can make per second.



 @{B}Bytes/event@{b} lets you set the number of bytes that the Spooler process

     can send to the printer per event. Sensible values lie between 1

     and 1000. Depending on the number of events to be handled per

     second, this value may have to be modified.



     @{I}Note:@{i}

     If the printer balks during printing, increase the number of

     @{B}Events@{b} or @{B}Bytes@{b}; if the printer slows down the operation of

     the program, decrease the values.





 The @{B}Driver...@{b} button serves for loading a new printer driver, just

     like a click on the printer icon at top left.



 The @{B}Load...@{b} button is used for loading new printer parameters from

     a previously saved text file, opening a fileselector-box to let

     you choose a suitable file.



 The @{B}@{Save ignore}...@{b} button serves for saving the parameters displayed in

     this dialog-box to a text file. Note that this does not include

     the printer driver.



@endnode





