@node "Dialogbox Suchen" "Search dialog-box"

@toc "The dialog-boxes"

@autorefoff

@{U}B.32  Search dialog-box                                PHOENIX Manager@{u}

@autorefon



The top three lines show the @{B}Database@{b}, @{B}Table@{b} and @{B}Index@{b} used for the

search.



 In the @{B}Term@{b} editable field you type in the term you wish to find;

     for tables it refers to the index used in the table.

     It is possible also to search for a given data record by its

     position instead of a term. For this the field has to be prefixed

     with the '#' character:



     @{I}Term     Meaning@{i}

@Line 6 39 0 0 1

     Joppich  @{Search ignore} for term 'Joppich'

     #1000    Jump to position 1000

     #+250    Jump 250 data records forward

     #-300    Jump 300 data records backward

@symbol "Full text search"



 With @{B}Full text search@{b} active, the search will be made through all

     fields without using the current index; such a search without

     an index takes appreciably more time.



     If you are not sure of the complete term to be searched for, nor

     know at which position of the field the term you are looking for

     lies, the use of the wildcards '?' for any one character and '*'

     for any number of arbitrary characters recommends itself. Thus

     to find 'Meier' for certain, no matter how it is spelt and in

     what position in a field the name was input, you should use

     '*M??er*' for the search term.



 @{B}Respect upper/lowercase@{b} is only available for @{B}Full text search@{b} and

     when active differentiates between capitals and lower case.



 @{B}Forwards@{b} looks for data records that are displayed after the present

     position in the window.



 @{B}Backwards@{b} looks for data records that are displayed earlier than the

     present position in the window.



@endnode





@node "Dialogbox Sortierung" "Sorting dialog-box"

@toc "The dialog-boxes"

@{U}B.33  Sorting dialog-box                               PHOENIX Manager@{u}



The top two lines show the @{B}Database@{b} and @{B}Table@{b} that sorting is to be

performed on.



 The @{B}Fields@{b} listbox displays all fields of the table. One field at

     a time in it can be clicked on and then a click on the @{B}>>>>>@{b}

     button transfers it to the @{B}Sort by@{b} box. For this the setting of

     the @{B}Sort@{b} radio buttons is respected.

     The same result can be achieved by a double-click on the listbox

     field. After the field is transferred it vanishes from the @{B}Fields@{b}

     listbox.



 The @{B}Sort by@{b} listbox shows those fields that have been transferred

     already from the @{B}Fields@{b} list. Additionally the sort direction to

     be used is shown, @{B}+@{b} meaning ascending and @{B}-@{b} descending order.



 A click on @{B}>>>>>@{b} transfers the next field from the @{B}Fields@{b} box to the

     @{B}Sort by@{b} box.



 A click on @{B}<<<<<@{b} transfers the last field from the @{B}Sort by@{b} box back

     to the @{B}Fields@{b} box.



 In the @{B}Sort@{b} area you can choose whether the next field to be trans-

     ferred to the @{B}Sort by@{b} box should use an @{B}Ascending@{b} or @{B}Descending@{b}

     sorting order. A double-click on one of the two buttons or its

     legend has the effect of transferring the currently selected

     field in the @{B}Fields@{b} box; naturally the corresponding sorting

     direction will be switched to beforehand.



 The @{B}@{New ignore}@{b} button clears the complete @{B}Sort by@{b} list and gives you the

     chance to start again.



@endnode





