@node "Dialogbox Benutzer-OberflÑche" "User interface dialog-box"

@toc "The dialog-boxes"

@{U}B.35  User interface dialog-box                        PHOENIX Manager@{u}



This appears when you select the @{B}User desktop@{b} entry in the main

Parameters menu.



 ˘ The @{B}Colours@{b} area lets you assign a colour to elements of the user

     interface desktop.



 @{B}Element@{b} shows the element whose colour is to be altered. You can

     select the element to be affected from the drop-down list.



 @{B}Colour@{b} offers a selection of up to 16 different colours for the

     element. Selection is only sensible providing the current screen

     resolution can display at least 16 colours.





 ˘ The @{B}Display@{b} area offers the possibility of determining the basic

     appearance of the user interface.



 If @{B}3D-look desktop@{b} is switched on (checkbox crossed) then the user

     interface will be drawn in a modern three-dimensional style.

     However this requires a screen resolution that is capable of

     displaying at least 16 colours.



 If @{B}Dialogs with frames@{b} is switched on, then the dialog-boxes will be

     provided with a 'picture frame'. This function too needs a screen

     resolution capable of displaying at least 16 colours.



 If @{B}Use standard fileselector@{b} is switched on, then the fileselector

     installed on the system will be used. With the checkbox uncrossed

     @{"PHOENIX's own fileselector" LINK "Dialogbox Dateiauswahl"} will be employed instead.





 ˘ The @{B}Control elements@{b} area gives the option of assigning various

     icon symbols to some elements of the user interface.



 @{B}Checkbox@{b} offers a selection of symbols to denote a chekbox.



 @{B}Radio button@{b} lets you choose a symbol to denote a radio button.



 @{B}Arrows@{b} lets you choose the appearance of arrows in listboxes and

     popup listboxes.





 ˘ The @{B}Desktop@{b} area offers options for changing the appearance of

     the desktop surface.



 @{B}Colour@{b} permits the selection of up to 16 different colours for the

     desktop background, provided you are working with a 16-colour or

     higher screen resolution. If the colour @{B}White@{b} is selected then

     you can not choose a fill-pattern (all would be white on white).



 @{B}Fill@{b} offers a selection of 8 different fill-patterns for the desktop

     background (but see above).



 If the @{B}Display in window@{b} checkbox is switched on (crossed), the

     Manager desktop will be placed in a plain window the next time

     you launch the program.



 Switching on @{B}Activate with click@{b} as well allows you to return to the

     Manager's desktop quickly from a database or a mask window by

     just clicking on it. Furthermore the desktop will be the topped

     window the next time you launch the program.



 By activating @{B}Display scroll bars@{b} as well as @{B}Display in window@{b}, the

     window will have the normal horizontal and vertical scroll bars

     at its bottom and right edge at the next program launch.





 ˘ The @{B}Buttons@{b} area lets you change the appearance of the large

     buttons in dialog-boxes (e.g. @{B}OK@{b}, @{B}Cancel@{b}, @{B}Help@{b} etc.).



 @{B}Rounded corners@{b} will be drawn for the buttons when the checkbox is

     crossed.



 @{B}Shadow width@{b} lets you add shadows of adjustable width by activating

     the checkbox and typing the desired width in the editable field;

     the larger the value the more the buttons seem to protrude from

     the screen plane. Note that this function is available only in

     16-colour resolutions and up and also only if @{B}3D-look desktop@{b}

     is active.





 ˘ The @{B}Standard@{b} button restores the appearance of all the elements

     to the default for the system.



@endnode





