@node "PHOENIX and OLGA"

@toc "Inhalt"

@{U}E  PHOENIX and OLGA                                    PHOENIX Manager@{u}



@{B}Introduction to OLGA@{b}



With OLGA ('@{B}O@{b}bject @{B}L@{b}inking for @{B}G@{b}EM @{B}A@{b}pplications') a new concept comes

into use under MagiC or other multitasking operating systems, just

like those that came into fashion on other computer platforms at the

time. Think of OLE from Microsoft or OpenDoc from Apple.



OLGA is a system extension for MagiC, MultiTOS, N.AES etc. that

permits the programs supporting it to access data objects jointly.



Here is apractical example of the advantages that OLGA offers:

Let us assume that you import a graphic into a graphics field in

Manager. Now you realise that the image has to be altered. Since

the Manager itself does not offer any drawing functions, you had

to do the following until now:

1. Export the graphic again.

2. Launch Pixart4 (for example - or any suitable graphics program,

   which can be specified in the OLGA.INF file).

3. Load graphic into Pixart4 and modify it.

4. @{Save ignore} the graphic and quit Pixart4.

5. Reimport the graphic into the data record.



This is far more elegant via OLGA. You first import the graphic into

Manager. A double-click on this graphic starts Pixart4 automatically

in parallel to Manager and the graphic can be modified immediately.

When saving the changes in Pixart4 the graphic in the input mask of

the Manager is updated automatically, without any actions being

necessary.



Or you type a long text into a mask. Now you want to make extensive

changes to this text, which would be quite a burden with Manager's

own, limited, editor. Just double-click on the Text field in the mask

and OLGA looks after the launch of the QED text editor (or similar -

again you can choose in OLGA.INF) in parallel and opens a window with

this text. You can now modify the text, and after saving it you will

now find the changes in the input mask immediately without having to

perform any further actions.



The OLGA protocol is executed by the parallel-launched and otherwise

invisible OLGA-Manager (OLGA.APP), which during the installation of

PHOENIX is installed in MagiC's @{Start ignore} folder on request (by default

in C:\GEMSYS\MAGIC\START).



OLGA is supported at present by PHOENIX, CAB, Texel, ArtWorx, Pixart4

and the editors Everest and QED, amongst others. Further programs will

follow.



@{B}OLGA in @{Designer ignore}@{b}



During the creation of input masks in @{"Designer" LINK "DESIGNER.HYP/Maskenfenster"} it is possible to

accommodate graphic objects in the masks. Thanks to OLGA it is simple

to make changes to these graphic objects. You just have to double-

click on the graphic. The @{B}Image size@{b} dialog-box appears; activating

the @{B}Edit@{b} button launches the OLGA-Server installed for the graphic

type (Pixart4 for bitmap images, ArtWorx for metafiles for instance)

in parallel to @{Designer ignore} and opens the graphic there for any modifi-

cations you wish to make. Once you have made them, save the graphic

again. The mask will be updated immediately in @{Designer ignore}.



@{B}OLGA in Manager@{b}



In Manager too the OLGA support is applied to the input mask. Here

various actions are possible.



With a double-click on a Text field the OLGA-Server for texts (QED by

default - can be changed in OLGA.INF) is launched and this text is

opened in it for modification. On saving the modified text in QED the

changes become visible immediately in Manager's input mask and the

data record will be marked as changed. With Change in the Record menu

of the Masks window menu-bar the changes will be saved to the

database.



A double-click on a graphic field will launch the OLGA-Server suitable

for the graphic format (Pixart4 for GEM images [.IMG] or ArtWorx for

metafiles [.GEM] for instance) in parallel to Manager and opens the

graphic there for any modifications you wish to make. Here too the

changes you have made become visible in the input mask as soon as you

have saved the graphic.



The functions listed above can be applied to @{"External file" LINK "DESIGNER.HYP/Data types" 40} type

fields as well. For this you should first double-click on the field

with the filename. The file will be displayed in a window. A double-

click on the window's contents transfers the file for modification

into the relevant OLGA-Server.



@endnode





