@node "Incorrect memory display"

@toc "Known errors in PHOENIX"

@{U}H.1  Incorrect memory display                          PHOENIX Manager@{u}



@{B}Has anyone noticed the PHOENIX has problems with TT-Ram >16 Mb? With

me the display has:



TOS 3.06

MEM: -32575k, TOT: -29199k



MiNT/N.AES

MEM: 32547k, TOT: -29559k@{b}



This is obviously completely wrong. It appears that there are still

faulty parts from SCRAP in this that were not corrected - a pretty

dumb error.



The explanation for this is that the resource (built into PHOENIX)

specifies an erroneous formatting string for sprintf. I have found

this in the Scrap project in the book from brothers Geiss.



It looks like this: 'MEM: %4d KB', but should be 'MEM: %4u KB'.



The memory size is specified in KB as a @{WORD ignore}, i.e. %4d results in a

number >32767 outputting a negative value; therefore there should be

%4u there. I have changed this in Scrap and then it worked, so it

should be a simple patch in PHOENIX that could be done without major

problems.



One could change this with a HEX editor or QED in binary mode. One

has to careful not to change the length of the character-string.



Statements are made without guarantee and at your own risk.



@endnode





@node "Auto-load a DB with password"

@toc "Known errors in PHOENIX"

@{U}H.2  Auto-load a DB with password                      PHOENIX Manager@{u}



@{B}There is still the error with the automatic loading of a DB with pass-

word in @{Designer ignore}. This results in a bad crash, partly only solvable

by a reset or switching the computer off and on again.@{b}



The reason is that the stack is too small for the many subprograms

nested within each other. Data is overwritten.



One can correct this - just patch the program header, i.e. enlarge

the BSS region.



@endnode





