@node "The SYSTEM.INF file"

@toc "Inhalt"

@{U}I  The SYSTEM.INF file                                 PHOENIX Manager@{u}



In the PHOENIX directory there is the folder SYSTEM which contains

the file SYSTEM.INF. This file contains information that Manager and

@{Designer ignore} can use for configuration of their user interface. So that

PHOENIX can access the file, you must copy the SYSTEM folder to a

GEMSYS folder on drive C.



Here follows a sample SYSTEM.INF file with an explanation of the

components (lines starting with a ';' are comments/explanations):



[Drives]

;<drive letter>=<descriptor>

;<descriptors are>:

;FD=Floppy disk drive

;HD=Hard disk drive

;CD=CD-ROM drive

;NET=Network mapped drive

;RD=RAM drive

;FDs and HDs are recognized by system and are therefore optional

A=FD

B=FD

C=HD

D=HD

E=HD

F=HD

G=NET

Y=CD

Z=RD



[IconMappings]

;<suffixes>=<img file without suffix>

APP;PRG;AC?;TOS;TTP=app

BIN=bin

GEM=gem

IMG=img

IND;DAT=ind

INF=inf

PRT;PRN=prt

TXT;ASC;C;DBS;DOC;H;ICO;LST;RPT=txt



[System]

AdaptBitmaps=1

GetVolumeNames=0

GDOSmaxDevice=40



Under @{B}[Drives]@{b} one can specify the types of the individual drives

more precisely. The new PHOENIX fileselector-box uses the information

stored here for displaying a suitable icon before each drive name. It

distinguishes between floppy drives (FD), hard disk (HD), CD-ROM (CD),

network drivwes (NET) and RAM-disks (RD). The assignment of floppy and

hard disk drives does not have to be made manually, since these are

recognised automatically by the system.

The syntax of the assignment is: @{B}Drive-ID=Drive type@{b}



@{B}[IconMappings]@{b} controls the allocation of file icons to the filetypes

used by the PHOENIX fileselector-box for display. Built into PHOENIX

are icons for the filetypes @{B}APP, PRG, ACC, TOS, TTP@{b} (descriptor @{B}app@{b}),

@{B}BIN@{b} (descriptor @{B}bin@{b}), @{B}GEM@{b} (descriptor @{B}gem@{b}), @{B}IMG@{b} (descriptor @{B}img@{b}),

@{B}IND, DAT@{b} (descriptor @{B}ind@{b}), @{B}INF@{b} (descriptor @{B}inf@{b}), @{B}PRT, PRN@{b} (descriptor

@{B}prt@{b}), @{B}TXT, ASC, C, DBS, DOC, H, ICO, LST, RPT@{b} (descriptor @{B}txt@{b}). You

can include further filetypes into the allocation.

The syntax for this is: @{B}Filetype1; Filetype2;...=decriptor@{b}.



You have the option of designing your own icons for these and other

filetypes. The filenames must follow the following rules:

The first characters must match the identifiers named above: so, for

instance @{B}APP@{b} for executable programs. There follows either a @{B}1@{b} for a

monochrome icon, a @{B}4@{b} for a 16-colour icon or an @{B}M@{b} for the

mask. Thus the file @{B}APP1.IMG@{b} contains the monochrome icon, the file

@{B}APP4.IMG@{b} the colour icon and the file @{B}APPM.IMG@{b} the mask for the icon

for executable programs.

These files are quite normal @{B}IMG@{b} files. The graphics should have a

size of 16x16 pixels. The mask is always a monochrome graphic in which

all pixels must be black that on selection of the icon later are not

to be shown in inverse video.

The IMG files must be stored in the same folder as SYSTEM.INF.



Under @{B}[System]@{b} there are two settings:

@{B}GetVolumeNames@{b} determines whether on launching Manager and

@{Designer ignore} the names of the connected drives should be asked for.

These then appear in PHOENIX's own fileselector-box for the purpose

of better identification. But if you are working with interchangeable

disk hard drives that, though connected, sometimes have no medium in

them, or when you work in a network in which all network drives are

not always accessible, then you should deactivate this option with

@{B}GetVolumeNames=0@{b}. Otherwise at program launch you would get an error

message for each inaccessible drive in the form 'Drive X does not

answer...' which you would have to acknowledge each time. By default

@{B}GetVolumeNames@{b} is switched on.

@symbol ari "AdaptBitmaps"



@{B}AdaptBitmaps@{b} is of interest to owners of graphics cards and MagiCMac

who work in more than 16 colours: If you assign the value @{B}1@{b} to

@{B}AdaptBitmaps@{b}, then on launching PHOENIX an adaptation of the internal

colour resources to the graphics card hardware being used will be

performed. This does, however, take a bit of time. If you use NVDI as

driver software for your graphics card, such adaptation is normally

not necessary. If the PHOENIX operating elements look strange after

the launch of the program, then it is imperative that you set this

value to @{B}1@{b}.

@symbol ari "GDOSmaxDevice"



With @{B}GDOSmaxDevice@{b} you can set the highest number of the GDOS device

driver that PHOENIX is to take into account. The preset is 100.

A restriction may be sensible because, for instance, I find that with

the STemulator the device driver 62 (Memory driver) causes a crash.

In the sample file above PHOENIX would search through device drivers

21 to 40 inclusive for available drivers.



@endnode





